# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: centrifugal-governor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Steam power has generally been superseded by the internal combustion engine or by electrical power drawn from an electrical grid.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The only steam installations that are in widespread use are the highly efficient thermal power plants used for generating electricity on a large scale.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] In contrast, the proposed steam engines may be for stationary, road, rail, or marine use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Although most references to "Modern Steam" apply to developments since the 1970s, certain aspects of advanced steam technology can be discerned throughout the 20th century, notably automatic boiler control along with rapid startup.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] In 1922, Abner Doble developed an electro-mechanical system that reacted simultaneously to steam temperature and pressure, starting and stopping the feed pumps whilst igniting and cutting out the burner according to boiler pressure.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The contraflow monotube boiler had a working pressure of 750–1,200 psi (5.17–8.27 MPa) but contained so little water in circulation as to present no risk of explosion.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] This type of boiler was continuously developed in the US, Britain and Germany throughout the 1930s and into the 1950s for use in cars, buses, trucks, railcars, shunting locomotives (US; switchers), a speedboat and, in 1933, a converted Travel Air 2000 biplane.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] In the UK, Sentinel Waggon Works developed a vertical water-tube boiler running at 275 psi (1.90 MPa) which was used in road vehicles, shunting locomotives and railcars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Steam could be raised much more quickly than with a conventional locomotive boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Trials of the Anderson condensing system took place on Britain's Southern Railway between 1930 and 1935.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Anderson condensing system uses a process known as mechanical vapor recompression.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] It was devised by a Glasgow marine engineer, Harry Percival Harvey Anderson.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The theory was that, by removing around 600 of the 970 British thermal units present in each pound of steam (1400 of the 2260 kilojoules in each kilogram), it would be possible to return the exhaust steam to the boiler by a pump which would consume only 1–2% of the engine's power output.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Between 1925 and 1927 Anderson, and another Glasgow engineer John McCullum (some sources give McCallum), conducted experiments on a stationary steam plant with encouraging results.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A company, Steam Heat Conservation (SHC), was formed and a demonstration of Anderson's system was arranged at Surbiton Electricity Generating Station.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] SHC was interested in applying the system to a railway locomotive and contacted Richard Maunsell of the Southern Railway.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell requested that a controlled test be carried out at Surbiton and this was done about 1929.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Maunsell's technical assistant, Harold Holcroft, was present and a fuel saving of 29% was recorded, compared to conventional atmospheric working.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Southern Railway converted SECR N class locomotive number A816 (later 1816 and 31816) to the Anderson system in 1930.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive underwent trials and initial results were encouraging.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The trials continued until 1934 but various problems arose, mostly with the fan for forced draught, and the project went no further.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The locomotive was converted back to standard form in 1935.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The work of French mechanical engineer André Chapelon in applying scientific analysis and a strive for thermal efficiency was an early example of advanced steam technology.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Chapelon's protégé Livio Dante Porta continued Chapelon's work.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Postwar in the late 1940s and 1950s some designers worked on modernising steam locomotives.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Argentinian engineer Livio Dante Porta in the development of Stephensonian railway locomotives incorporating advanced steam technology was a precursor of the 'Modern Steam' movement from 1948.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Where possible, Porta much preferred to design new locomotives, but more often in practice he was forced to radically update old ones to incorporate the new technology.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] 1949 by Oliver Bulleid and the British Rail ‘Standard’ class steam locomotives of the 1950s by Robert Riddles, particularly the BR Standard Class 9F, were used to trial new steam locomotive design features, including the Franco-Crosti boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] On moving to Ireland, Bulleid also designed CIÉ No.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Sir Biscoe Tritton Lecture, given by Roger Waller, of the DLM company to the Institute of Mechanical Engineers in 2003 gives an idea of how problems in steam power are being addressed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Waller refers mainly to some rack and pinion mountain railway locomotives that were newly built from 1992 to 1998.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] They were developed for three companies in Switzerland and Austria and continued to work on two of these lines as of 2008.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The new steam locomotives burn the same grade of light oil as their diesel counterparts, and all demonstrate the same advantages of ready availability and reduced labour cost; at the same time, they have been shown to greatly reduce air and ground pollution.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Their economic superiority has meant that they have largely replaced the diesel locomotives and railcars previously operating the line; additionally, steam locomotives are a tourist attraction.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A parallel line of development was the return to steam power of the old Lake Geneva paddle steamer *Montreux* that had been refitted with a diesel-electric engine in the 1960s.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Economic aims similar to those achieved with the rack locomotives were pursued through automatic control of the light-oil-fired boiler and remote control of the engine from the bridge, enabling the steamship to be operated by a crew of the same size as a motor ship.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A power unit based on advanced steam technology burning fossil fuel will inevitably emit carbon dioxide, a long-lasting greenhouse gas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] However, significant reductions of other pollutants such as CO and NOx are achievable by steam compared to other combustion technologies, since it does not involve explosive combustion, thus removing the need for add-ons (such as filters) or special preparation of fuel.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] If renewable fuel such as wood or other biofuel is used then the system could be carbon neutral.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The use of biofuel remains controversial; however, liquid biofuels are easier to manufacture for steam plant than for diesels as they do not demand the stringent fuel standards required to protect diesel injectors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] In principle, combustion and power delivery of steam plant can be considered separate stages.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] High overall thermal efficiency may be difficult to achieve, largely due to the extra stage of generating a working fluid between combustion and power delivery attributable mainly to leakages and heat losses.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The separation of the processes allows specific problems to be addressed at each stage without revising the whole system every time.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] For instance, the boiler or steam generator can be adapted to use any heat source, whether obtained from solid, liquid or gaseous fuel, and can use waste heat.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Whatever the choice, it will have no direct effect on the design of the engine unit, as that only ever has to deal with steam.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] This project mainly includes combined electrical generation and heating systems for private homes and small villages burning wood or bamboo chips.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] This is intended to replace 2-stroke donkey engines and small diesel power plants.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Drastic reduction in noise level is one immediate benefit of a steam-powered small plant.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Ted Pritchard, of Melbourne, Australia, was intensively developing this type of unit from 2002 until his death in 2007.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The company Pritchard Power (now Uniflow Power) stated in 2010 that they continue to develop the stationary S5000, and that a prototype had been built and was being tested, and designs were being refined for market ready products.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Until 2006 a German company called *Enginion* was actively developing a *Steamcell*, a micro CHP unit about the size of a PC tower for domestic use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] It seems that by 2008 it had merged with Berlin company AMOVIS.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Since 2012, a French company, EXOES, is selling to industrial firms a Rankine Cycle, patented, engine, which is designed to work with many fuels such as concentrated solar power, biomass, or fossil.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The system, called "SHAPE" for Sustainable Heat And Power Engine, converts the heat into electricity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The SHAPE engine is suitable for embedded, and stationary, applications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A SHAPE engine has been integrated into a biomass boiler, and into a Concentrated solar power system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The company is planning to work with automobile manufactures, long-haul truck manufactures, and railway corporations.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A similar unit is marketed by Powertherm, a subsidiary of Spilling (see below).
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A company in India manufactures steam-powered generators in a range of sizes from 4 hp to 50 hp.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] They also offer a number of different mills that can be powered by their engines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] In matter of technology, notice that the Quasiturbine is a uniflow rotary steam engine where steam intakes in hot areas, while exhausting in cold areas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Spilling company produces a variety of small fixed stationary plant adapted to biomass combustion or power derived from waste heat or pressure recovery.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The Finnish company Steammotor Finland has developed a small rotary steam engine that runs with 800 kW steam generator.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The engines are planned to produce electricity in wood chip fired power plants.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] According to the company, the steam engine named *Quadrum* generates 27% efficiency and runs with 180 °C steam at 8 bar pressure, while a corresponding steam turbine produces just 15% efficiency, requires steam temperature of 240 °C and pressure of 40 bar.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The high efficiency comes from a patented crank mechanism, that gives a smooth, pulseless torque.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] The company believes that by further developing the construction there is potential to reach as high efficiency as 30–35%.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] During the first 1970s oil crisis, a number of investigations into steam technology were initiated by large automobile corporations although as the crisis died down, impetus was soon lost.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Australian engineer Ted Pritchard's main field of research from the late 1950s until the 1970s was the building of several efficient steam power units working on the uniflow system adapted to a small truck and two cars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] One of the cars was achieving the lowest emissions figures of that time.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] All these engines made heavy use of flameless ceramic heat cells both for the steam generator and at strategic boost points where steam was injected into the cylinder(s).
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A design mounted on power bogies with compact water-tube boiler similar to Sentinel designs of the 1930s.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Example: Sentinel-Cammell locomotive (right).
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Both 52 8055 and the proposed 5AT are of conventional layout, with the cab at the back, while the ACE 3000 had the cab located at the front.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Other approaches are possible, especially with liquid fuel firing.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] This is a well-tried design with the potential for a large power output and would provide the driver good visibility.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Another well-tried design with large power potential.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] A future design could include shorter water tanks, and a cab at each end, to give the driver a good view in either direction.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] Another proposal for advanced steam technology is to revive the fireless locomotive, which runs on stored steam independently pre-generated.
[src:centrifugal-governor/advanced-steam-technology] An example is the Solar Steam Train project in Sacramento, California.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace did extensive fieldwork, starting in the Amazon River basin.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was considered the 19th century's leading expert on the geographical distribution of animal species, and is sometimes called the "father of biogeography", or more specifically of zoogeography.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace was one of the leading evolutionary thinkers of the 19th century, working on warning coloration in animals and reinforcement (sometimes known as the Wallace effect), a way that natural selection could contribute to speciation by encouraging the development of barriers against hybridisation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1864 he was the first to propose that during the later stages of human evolution natural selection would have primarily acted on mental faculties rather than on the physical form.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's 1904 book *Man's Place in the Universe* was the first serious attempt by a biologist to evaluate the likelihood of life on other planets.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He also had a scientific interest in the possibly of life on Mars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Aside from scientific work, he was a social activist, critical of what he considered to be the unjust social and economic systems of 19th-century Britain and later in life became an active socialist.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His advocacy of spiritualism and mind–body dualism strained his relationship with other scientists.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was one of the first prominent scientists to raise concerns over the environmental impact of human activity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He wrote prolifically on both scientific and social issues; his account of his adventures and observations during his explorations in Southeast Asia, *The Malay Archipelago*, was first published in 1869.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It continues to be both popular and highly regarded.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Alfred Russel Wallace was born on 8 January 1823 in Llanbadoc, Monmouthshire.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He was the eighth of nine children born to Mary Anne Wallace (née Greenell) and Thomas Vere Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His mother was English, while his father was of Scottish ancestry.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His family claimed a connection to William Wallace, a leader of Scottish forces during the Wars of Scottish Independence in the 13th century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's father graduated in law but never practised it.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He owned some income-generating property, but bad investments and failed business ventures resulted in a steady deterioration of the family's financial position.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's mother was from a middle-class family of Hertford, to which place his family moved when Wallace was five years old.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He attended Hertford Grammar School until 1837, when he reached the age of 14, the normal leaving age for a pupil not going on to university.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace then moved to London to board with his older brother John, a 19-year-old apprentice builder.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] This was a stopgap measure until William, his oldest brother, was ready to take him on as an apprentice surveyor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While in London, Alfred attended lectures and read books at the London Mechanics Institute.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Here he was exposed to the radical political ideas of the Welsh social reformer Robert Owen and of the English-born political theorist Thomas Paine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He left London in 1837 to live with William and work as his apprentice for six years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They moved repeatedly to different places in Mid-Wales.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Then at the end of 1839, they moved to Kington, Herefordshire, near the Welsh border, before eventually settling at Neath in Wales.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Between 1840 and 1843, Wallace worked as a land surveyor in the countryside of the west of England and Wales.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The natural history of his surroundings aroused his interest; from 1841 he collected flowers and plants as an amateur botanist.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One result of Wallace's early travels is a modern controversy about his nationality.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Since he was born in Monmouthshire, some sources have considered him to be Welsh.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Other historians have questioned this because neither of his parents were Welsh, his family only briefly lived in Monmouthshire, the Welsh people Wallace knew in his childhood considered him to be English, and because he consistently referred to himself as English rather than Welsh.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One Wallace scholar has stated that the most reasonable interpretation is therefore that he was an Englishman born in Wales.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1843 Wallace's father died, and a decline in demand for surveying meant William's business no longer had work available.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] For a short time Wallace was unemployed, then early in 1844 he was engaged by the Collegiate School in Leicester to teach drawing, mapmaking, and surveying.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He had already read George Combe's *The Constitution of Man*, and after Spencer Hall lectured on mesmerism, Wallace as well as some of the older pupils tried it out.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent many hours at the town library in Leicester; he read Thomas Robert Malthus's *An Essay on the Principle of Population*, Alexander von Humboldt's *Personal Narrative*, Charles Lyell's *Principles of Geology* and Charles Darwin's *The Voyage of the* Beagle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] One evening Wallace met the entomologist Henry Walter Bates, who was 19 years old, and had published an 1843 paper on beetles in *The Zoologist*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He befriended Wallace and started him collecting insects.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] When Wallace's brother William died in March 1845, Wallace left his teaching position to assume control of his brother's firm in Neath, but his brother John and he were unable to make the business work.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After a few months, he found work as a civil engineer for a nearby firm that was working on a survey for a proposed railway in the Vale of Neath.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace's work on the survey was largely outdoors in the countryside, allowing him to indulge his new passion for collecting insects.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace persuaded his brother John to join him in starting another architecture and civil engineering firm.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It carried out projects including the design of a building for the Neath Mechanics' Institute, founded in 1843.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During this period, he exchanged letters with Bates about books.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] By the end of 1845, Wallace was convinced by Robert Chambers's anonymously published treatise on progressive development, *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation*, but he found Bates was more critical.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] William Jevons, the founder of the Neath institute, was impressed by Wallace and persuaded him to give lectures there on science and engineering.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the autumn of 1846, Wallace and his brother John purchased a cottage near Neath, where they lived with their mother and sister Fanny.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Inspired by the chronicles of earlier and contemporary travelling naturalists, Wallace decided to travel abroad.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They therefore engaged as their agent Samuel Stevens who would advertise and arrange sales to institutions and private collectors, for a commission of 20% on sales plus 5% on despatching freight and remittances of money.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1848, Wallace and Bates left for Brazil aboard the *Mischief*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They intended to collect insects and other animal specimens in the Amazon rainforest for their private collections, selling the duplicates to museums and collectors back in Britain to fund the trip.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace hoped to gather evidence of the transmutation of species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Bates and he spent most of their first year collecting near Belém, then explored inland separately, occasionally meeting to discuss their findings.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1849, they were briefly joined by another young explorer, the botanist Richard Spruce, along with Wallace's younger brother Herbert.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Herbert soon left (dying two years later from yellow fever), but Spruce, like Bates, would spend over ten years collecting in South America.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent four years exploring the Amazon river and its tributary the Rio Negro, collecting specimens and making notes on the peoples and languages he encountered as well as the geography, flora, and fauna..
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace spent August 1850 through May 1852 on the Rio Negro using his surveying skills to chart it and its tributary, the Uaupés, with sextant and compass.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace ascended the Uaupés all the way into Colombia.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On 12 July 1852, Wallace embarked for the UK on the brig *Helen*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After 25 days at sea, the ship's cargo caught fire, and the crew was forced to abandon ship.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] All the specimens Wallace had on the ship, mostly collected during the last, and most interesting, two years of his trip, were lost.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He managed to save a few notes and pencil sketches, but little else.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace and the crew spent ten days in an open boat before being picked up by the brig *Jordeson*, which was sailing from Cuba to London.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The *Jordeson*'s provisions were strained by the unexpected passengers, but after a difficult passage on short rations, the ship reached its destination on 1 October 1852.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The lost collection had been insured for £200 by Stevens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After his return to Britain, Wallace spent 18 months in London living on the insurance payment, and selling a few specimens that had been shipped home.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During this period, despite having lost almost all the notes from his South American expedition, he wrote six academic papers (including "On the Monkeys of the Amazon") and two books, *Palm Trees of the Amazon and Their Uses* and *Travels on the Amazon*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] At the same time, he made connections with several other British naturalists.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Bates and others were collecting in the Amazon area, Wallace was more interested in new opportunities in the Malay Archipelago as demonstrated by the travel writings of Ida Laura Pfeiffer, and valuable insect specimens she collected which Stevens sold as her agent.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In March 1853 Wallace wrote to Sir James Brooke, Rajah of Sarawak, who was then in London, and who arranged assistance in Sarawak for Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In June Wallace wrote to Murchison at the Royal Geographical Society (RGS) for support, proposing to again fund his exploring entirely from sale of duplicate collections.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He later recalled that, while researching in the insect-room of the British Museum, he was introduced to Darwin and they "had a few minutes' conversation." After presenting a paper and a large map of the Rio Negro to the RGS, Wallace was elected a Fellow of the society on 27 February 1854.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Free passage arranged on Royal Navy ships was stalled by the Crimean War, but eventually the RGS funded first class travel by P&O steamships.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace and a young assistant, Charles Allen, embarked at Southampton on 4 March 1854.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After the overland journey to Suez and another change of ship at Ceylon they disembarked at Singapore on 19 April 1854.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] From 1854 to 1862, Wallace travelled around the islands of the Malay Archipelago or East Indies (now Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His main objective "was to obtain specimens of natural history, both for my private collection and to supply duplicates to museums and amateurs".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In addition to Allen, he "generally employed one or two, and sometimes three Malay servants" as assistants, and paid large numbers of local people at various places to bring specimens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His total was 125,660 specimens, most of which were insects including more than 83,000 beetles.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Several thousand of the specimens represented species new to science.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Overall, more than thirty men worked for him at some stage as full-time paid collectors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He also hired guides, porters, cooks and boat crews, so well over 100 individuals worked for him.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After collecting expeditions to Bukit Timah Hill in Singapore, and to Malacca, Wallace and Allen reached Sarawak in October 1854, and were welcomed at Kuching by Sir James Brooke's (then) heir Captain John Brooke.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace hired a Malay named Ali as a general servant and cook, and spent the early 1855 wet season in a small Dyak house at the foot of Mount Santubong, overlooking a branch outlet of the Sarawak River.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He read about species distribution, notes on Pictets's Palaeontology, and wrote his "Sarawak Paper".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In March he moved to the Simunjon coal-works, operated by the Borneo Company under Ludvig Verner Helms, and supplemented collecting by paying workers a cent for each insect.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] A specimen of the previously unknown gliding tree frog *Rhacophorus nigropalmatus* (now called Wallace's flying frog) came from a Chinese workman who told Wallace that it glided down.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Local people also assisted with shooting orangutans.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] They spent time with Sir James, then in February 1856 Allen chose to stay on with the missionaries at Kuching.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On reaching Singapore in May 1856, Wallace hired a bird-skinner.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] With Ali as cook, they collected for two days on Bali, then from 17 June to 30 August on Lombok.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In December 1856, Darwin had written to contacts worldwide to get specimens for his continuing research into variation under domestication.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] At Lombok's port city, Ampanam, Wallace wrote telling his agent, Stevens, about specimens shipped, including a domestic duck variety "for Mr.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Stevens arranged publication of relevant paragraphs in the January 1857 issue of *The Zoologist*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After further investigation, the zoogeographical boundary eventually became known as the Wallace Line.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Ali became Wallace's most trusted assistant, a skilled collector and researcher.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace collected and preserved the delicate insect specimens, while most of the birds were collected and prepared by his assistants; of those, Ali collected and prepared around 5000.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While exploring the archipelago, Wallace refined his thoughts about evolution, and had his famous insight on natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1858 he sent an article outlining his theory to Darwin; it was published, along with a description of Darwin's theory, that same year.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Accounts of Wallace's studies and adventures were eventually published in 1869 as *The Malay Archipelago*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] This became one of the most popular books of scientific exploration of the 19th century, and has never been out of print.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] It was praised by scientists such as Darwin (to whom the book was dedicated), by Lyell, and by non-scientists such as the novelist Joseph Conrad.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Conrad called the book his "favorite bedside companion" and used information from it for several of his novels, especially *Lord Jim*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] A set of 80 bird skeletons Wallace collected in Indonesia are held in the Cambridge University Museum of Zoology, and described as of exceptional historical significance.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1862, Wallace returned to Britain, where he moved in with his sister Fanny Sims and her husband Thomas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While recovering from his travels, Wallace organised his collections and gave numerous lectures about his adventures and discoveries to scientific societies such as the Zoological Society of London.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Later that year, he visited Darwin at Down House, and became friendly with both Lyell and the philosopher Herbert Spencer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During the 1860s, Wallace wrote papers and gave lectures defending natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He corresponded with Darwin about topics including sexual selection, warning coloration, and the possible effect of natural selection on hybridisation and the divergence of species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1865, he began investigating spiritualism.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] After a year of courtship, Wallace became engaged in 1864 to a young woman whom, in his autobiography, he would only identify as Miss L.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Miss L. was the daughter of Lewis Leslie who played chess with Wallace, but to Wallace's great dismay, she broke off the engagement.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace had been introduced to Mitten through the botanist Richard Spruce, who had befriended Wallace in Brazil and who was a friend of Annie Mitten's father, William Mitten, an expert on mosses.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1872, Wallace built the Dell, a house of concrete, on land he leased in Grays in Essex, where he lived until 1876.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the late 1860s and 1870s, Wallace was very concerned about the financial security of his family.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] While he was in the Malay Archipelago, the sale of specimens had brought in a considerable amount of money, which had been carefully invested by the agent who sold the specimens for Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On his return to the UK, Wallace made a series of bad investments in railways and mines that squandered most of the money, and he found himself badly in need of the proceeds from the publication of *The Malay Archipelago*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Despite assistance from his friends, he was never able to secure a permanent salaried position such as a curatorship in a museum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] To remain financially solvent, Wallace worked grading government examinations, wrote 25 papers for publication between 1872 and 1876 for various modest sums, and was paid by Lyell and Darwin to help edit some of their works.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1876, Wallace needed a £500 advance from the publisher of *The Geographical Distribution of Animals* to avoid having to sell some of his personal property.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Darwin was very aware of Wallace's financial difficulties and lobbied long and hard to get Wallace awarded a government pension for his lifetime contributions to science.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] When the £200 annual pension was awarded in 1881, it helped to stabilise Wallace's financial position by supplementing the income from his writings.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1881, Wallace was elected as the first president of the newly formed Land Nationalisation Society.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In the next year, he published a book, *Land Nationalisation; Its Necessity and Its Aims*, on the subject.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1889, Wallace read *Looking Backward* by Edward Bellamy and declared himself a socialist, despite his earlier foray as a speculative investor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace opposed eugenics, an idea supported by other prominent 19th-century evolutionary thinkers, on the grounds that contemporary society was too corrupt and unjust to allow any reasonable determination of who was fit or unfit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace wrote repeatedly on the dangers and wastefulness of militarism.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace criticised the UK's free trade policies for the negative impact they had on working-class people.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1898, He wrote a paper advocating a pure paper money system, not backed by silver or gold, which impressed the economist Irving Fisher so much that he dedicated his 1920 book *Stabilizing the Dollar* to Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace wrote in support of women's suffrage.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1898, Wallace published *The Wonderful Century: Its Successes and Its Failures*, about developments in the 19th century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Wallace continued his social activism for the rest of his life, publishing the book *The Revolt of Democracy* just weeks before his death.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In 1880, he published *Island Life* as a sequel to *The Geographic Distribution of Animals*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] In November 1886, Wallace began a ten-month trip to the United States to give a series of popular lectures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Most of the lectures were on Darwinism (evolution through natural selection), but he also gave speeches on biogeography, spiritualism, and socio-economic reform.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] During the trip, he was reunited with his brother John who had emigrated to California years before.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He spent a day touring Yosemite in the company of John Muir.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Years later Muir would credit his conversation with Wallace with sparking his interest in visiting the Amazon basin.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] He met many other prominent American naturalists and viewed their collections.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His 1889 book *Darwinism* used information he collected on his American trip and information he had compiled for the lectures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] On 7 November 1913, Wallace died at home, aged 90, in the country house he called Old Orchard, which he had built a decade earlier.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] His death was widely reported in the press.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] *The New York Times* called him "the last of the giants [belonging] to that wonderful group of intellectuals composed of Darwin, Huxley, Spencer, Lyell, Owen, and other scientists, whose daring investigations revolutionized and evolutionized the thought of the century".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Some of Wallace's friends suggested that he be buried in Westminster Abbey, but his wife followed his wishes and had him buried in the small cemetery at Broadstone, Dorset.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] Several prominent British scientists formed a committee to have a medallion of Wallace placed in Westminster Abbey near where Darwin had been buried.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p01] The medallion was unveiled on 1 November 1915.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace began his career as a travelling naturalist already believing in the transmutation of species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The concept had been advocated by Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, Erasmus Darwin, and Robert Grant, among others.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It was widely discussed, but not generally accepted by leading naturalists, and was considered to have radical, even revolutionary connotations.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Prominent anatomists and geologists such as Georges Cuvier, Richard Owen, Adam Sedgwick, and Lyell attacked transmutation vigorously.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It has been suggested that Wallace accepted the idea of the transmutation of species in part because he was always inclined to favour radical ideas in politics, religion and science, and because he was unusually open to marginal, even fringe, ideas in science.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was profoundly influenced by Robert Chambers's *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation*, a controversial work of popular science published anonymously in 1844.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It advocated an evolutionary origin for the Solar System, the Earth, and living things.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace wrote to Henry Bates in 1845 describing it as "an ingenious hypothesis strongly supported by some striking facts and analogies, but which remains to be proven by ... more research".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace planned fieldwork to test the evolutionary hypothesis that closely related species should inhabit neighbouring territories.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] During his work in the Amazon basin, he came to realise that geographical barriers—such as the Amazon and its major tributaries—often separated the ranges of closely allied species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He included these observations in his 1853 paper "On the Monkeys of the Amazon".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Near the end of the paper he asked the question, "Are very closely allied species ever separated by a wide interval of country?".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For sometime Wallace had been compiling notes for an argument against the concept of new species being introduced through progressive creationism found in Charles Lyell's *Principles of Geology*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This was Lyell's rebuttal to transmutational ideas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When Wallace read an 1854 paper written by Edward Forbes that proposed an even more quasi-mystical form of progressive creationism he decided to write a response.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In February 1855, while working in Sarawak on the island of Borneo, Wallace wrote "On the Law which has Regulated the Introduction of New Species".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The paper was published in the *Annals and Magazine of Natural History* in September 1855.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In this paper, he discussed observations of the geographic and geologic distribution of both living and fossil species, a field that became biogeography.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This paper foreshadowed the momentous paper he would write three years later.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The paper challenged Lyell's belief that species were immutable.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Darwin had written to him in 1842 expressing support for transmutation, Lyell had continued to be strongly opposed to the idea.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Around the start of 1856, he told Darwin about Wallace's paper, as did Edward Blyth who thought it "Good!
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace has, I think put the matter well; and according to his theory the various domestic races of animals have been fairly developed into *species*." Despite this hint, Darwin mistook Wallace's conclusion for the progressive creationism of the time, writing that it was "nothing very new ...
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Uses my simile of tree [but] it seems all creation with him." Lyell was more impressed, and opened a notebook on species in which he grappled with the consequences, particularly for human ancestry.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had already shown his theory to their mutual friend Joseph Hooker and now, for the first time spelt out the full details of natural selection to Lyell.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Lyell could not agree, he urged Darwin to publish to establish priority.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin demurred at first, but began writing up a *species sketch* of his continuing work in May 1856.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] By February 1858, Wallace had been convinced by his biogeographical research in the Malay Archipelago that evolution was real.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He later wrote in his autobiography that the problem was of how species change from one well-marked form to another.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He stated that it was while he was in bed with a fever that he thought about Malthus's idea of positive checks on human population, and had the idea of natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His autobiography says that he was on the island of Ternate at the time; but the evidence of his journal suggests that he was in fact on the island of Gilolo.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] From 1858 to 1861, he rented a house on Ternate from the Dutchman Maarten Dirk van Renesse van Duivenbode, which he used as a base for expeditions to other islands such as Gilolo.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace had once briefly met Darwin, and was one of the correspondents whose observations Darwin used to support his own theories.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Wallace's first letter to Darwin has been lost, Wallace carefully kept the letters he received.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The second letter, dated 22 December 1857, said how glad he was that Wallace was theorising about distribution, adding that "without speculation there is no good and original observation" but commented that "I believe I go much further than you".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace believed this and sent Darwin his February 1858 essay, "On the Tendency of Varieties to Depart Indefinitely From the Original Type", asking Darwin to review it and pass it to Charles Lyell if he thought it worthwhile.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although Wallace had sent several articles for journal publication during his travels through the Malay archipelago, the Ternate essay was in a private letter.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin received the essay on 18 June 1858.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although the essay did not use Darwin's term "natural selection", it did outline the mechanics of an evolutionary divergence of species from similar ones due to environmental pressures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In this sense, it was very similar to the theory that Darwin had worked on for 20 years, but had yet to publish.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin sent the manuscript to Charles Lyell with a letter saying "he could not have made a better short abstract!
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's essay was presented to the Linnean Society of London on 1 July 1858, along with excerpts from an essay which Darwin had disclosed privately to Hooker in 1847 and a letter Darwin had written to Asa Gray in 1857.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Communication with Wallace in the far-off Malay Archipelago involved months of delay, so he was not part of this rapid publication.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace accepted the arrangement after the fact, happy that he had been included at all, and never expressed bitterness in public or in private.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin's social and scientific status was far greater than Wallace's, and it was unlikely that, without Darwin, Wallace's views on evolution would have been taken seriously.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Lyell and Hooker's arrangement relegated Wallace to the position of co-discoverer, and he was not the social equal of Darwin or the other prominent British natural scientists.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] All the same, the joint reading of their papers on natural selection associated Wallace with the more famous Darwin.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This, combined with Darwin's (as well as Hooker's and Lyell's) advocacy on his behalf, would give Wallace greater access to the highest levels of the scientific community.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The reaction to the reading was muted, with the president of the Linnean Society remarking in May 1859 that the year had not been marked by any striking discoveries; but, with Darwin's publication of *On the Origin of Species* later in 1859, its significance became apparent.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When Wallace returned to the UK, he met Darwin.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Although some of Wallace's opinions in the ensuing years would test Darwin's patience, they remained friends and frequent correspondents for the rest of Darwin's life.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Over the years, a few people have questioned this version of events.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the early 1980s, two books, one by Arnold Brackman and another by John Langdon Brooks, suggested not only that there had been a conspiracy to rob Wallace of his proper credit, but that Darwin had actually stolen a key idea from Wallace to finish his own theory.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These claims have been examined and found unconvincing by a number of scholars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Shipping schedules show that, contrary to these accusations, Wallace's letter could not have been delivered earlier than the date shown in Darwin's letter to Lyell.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After Wallace returned to England in 1862, he became one of the staunchest defenders of Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In an incident in 1863 that particularly pleased Darwin, Wallace published the short paper "Remarks on the Rev.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Haughton's Paper on the Bee's Cell, And on the Origin of Species".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This rebutted a paper by a professor of geology at the University of Dublin that had sharply criticised Darwin's comments in the *Origin* on how hexagonal honey bee cells could have evolved through natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] An even longer defence was an 1867 article in the *Quarterly Journal of Science*, "Creation by Law".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It reviewed George Campbell, the 8th Duke of Argyll's book, *The Reign of Law*, which aimed to refute natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After an 1870 meeting of the British Science Association, Wallace wrote to Darwin complaining that there were "no opponents left who know anything of natural history, so that there are none of the good discussions we used to have".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Explorers in Madagascar had discovered the orchid *Angraecum sesquipedale*, with a sixteen-inch nectary.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin predicted the existence of a moth with a proboscis long enough to pollinate it.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Historians of science have noted that, while Darwin considered the ideas in Wallace's paper to be essentially the same as his own, there were differences.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin emphasised competition between individuals of the same species to survive and reproduce, whereas Wallace emphasised environmental pressures on varieties and species forcing them to become adapted to their local conditions, leading populations in different locations to diverge.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bowler has suggested that in the paper he mailed to Darwin, Wallace might have been discussing group selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Against this, Malcolm Kottler showed that Wallace was indeed discussing individual variation and selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others have noted that Wallace appeared to have envisioned natural selection as a kind of feedback mechanism that kept species and varieties adapted to their environment (now called 'stabilizing", as opposed to 'directional' selection).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] They point to a largely overlooked passage of Wallace's famous 1858 paper, in which he likened "this principle ... [to] the centrifugal governor of the steam engine, which checks and corrects any irregularities".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The cybernetician and anthropologist Gregory Bateson observed in the 1970s that, although writing it only as an example, Wallace had "probably said the most powerful thing that'd been said in the 19th Century".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bateson revisited the topic in his 1979 book *Mind and Nature: A Necessary Unity*, and other scholars have continued to explore the connection between natural selection and systems theory.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Warning colouration was one of Wallace's contributions to the evolutionary biology of animal colouration.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1867, Darwin wrote to Wallace about a problem in explaining how some caterpillars could have evolved conspicuous colour schemes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had come to believe that many conspicuous animal colour schemes were due to sexual selection, but he saw that this could not apply to caterpillars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace responded that he and Bates had observed that many of the most spectacular butterflies had a peculiar odour and taste, and that he had been told by John Jenner Weir that birds would not eat a certain kind of common white moth because they found it unpalatable.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Since the moth was as conspicuous at dusk as a coloured caterpillar in daylight, it seemed likely that the conspicuous colours served as a warning to predators and thus could have evolved through natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At a later meeting of the Entomological Society, and in a letter published in *Field* magazine, Wallace asked for any evidence anyone might have on the topic.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1869, Weir published data from experiments and observations involving brightly coloured caterpillars that supported Wallace's idea.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace attributed less importance than Darwin to sexual selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One area where he debated Darwin involved explaining sexual dimorphism in the colouration and nesting behaviour of many bird species where males are more brightly coloured than females.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin attributed this to sexual selection by females between competing males.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the 1860s Wallace wrote a series of papers that emphasized instead selective pressure from predation for drab colouration in females that spend a lot of time sitting on nests.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In his 1878 book *Tropical Nature and Other Essays*, he wrote extensively about the colouration of animals and plants, and proposed alternative explanations for a number of cases Darwin had attributed to sexual selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He revisited the topic at length in his 1889 book *Darwinism*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1890, he wrote a critical review in *Nature* of his friend Edward Bagnall Poulton's *The Colours of Animals* which supported Darwin on sexual selection, attacking especially Poulton's claims on the "aesthetic preferences of the insect world".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1889, Wallace wrote the book *Darwinism*, which explained and defended natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In it, he proposed the hypothesis that natural selection could drive the reproductive isolation of two varieties by encouraging the development of barriers against hybridisation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Thus it might contribute to the development of new species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He suggested the following scenario: When two populations of a species had diverged beyond a certain point, each adapted to particular conditions, hybrid offspring would be less adapted than either parent form and so natural selection would tend to eliminate the hybrids.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Furthermore, under such conditions, natural selection would favour the development of barriers to hybridisation, as individuals that avoided hybrid matings would tend to have more fit offspring, and thus contribute to the reproductive isolation of the two incipient species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This idea came to be known as the Wallace effect, later called reinforcement.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was motivated to spell the idea out in detail in 1889 in response to a paper by George Romanes that suggested that natural selection alone was insufficient to explain the separation of incipient species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace had suggested to Darwin that natural selection could play a role in preventing hybridisation in private correspondence as early as 1868, but had not worked it out in detail.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It continues to be a topic of research in evolutionary biology today, with both computer simulation and empirical results supporting its validity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In January 1864 Wallace presented a paper, "On the Varieties of Man in the Malay Archipelago", to the Ethnological Society of London.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This paper summarized his ethnological observations during his travels in the East Indies.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace stated that the people in the archipelago could be divided into two groups.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The first were members of what he called the Malay race and the second were members of the Papuan race.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He described the physical, linguistic, and cultural differences between them, and he traced an east west dividing line that separated the 2 groups.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He compared this with the famous dividing line he had discovered between Asian and Australian affiliated faunas, suggesting that the distribution of human races could be explained by the geographical history of a region the same way as the biogeographical distribution of species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A few weeks later he presented a follow up paper, "The Origin of Human Races and the Antiquity of Man Deduced from the Theory of 'Natural Selection'" to the Anthropological Society of London, applying the theory of natural selection to humankind.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin had not yet publicly addressed the subject, although Thomas Huxley had in *Evidence as to Man's Place in Nature*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace explained the apparent stability of the human stock by pointing to the vast gap in cranial capacities between humans and the great apes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Unlike some other Darwinists, including Darwin himself, he did not "regard modern primitives as almost filling the gap between man and ape".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He saw the evolution of humans in two stages: achieving a bipedal posture that freed the hands to carry out the dictates of the brain, and the "recognition of the human brain as a totally new factor in the history of life".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace seems to have been the first evolutionist to propose that the human brain effectively made further specialisation of the body unnecessary.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin would treat this idea at length in his 1871 work *The Descent of Man, and Selection in Relation to Sex*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace wrote the paper to address the debate between the supporters of monogenism, the belief that all human races shared a common ancestor and were part of one species, and the supporters of polygenism, who held that different races had separate origins and were different species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's anthropological observations of Native Americans in the Amazon, and especially his time living among the Dayak people of Borneo, had convinced him that human beings were a single species with a common ancestor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He still felt that natural selection might have continued to act on mental faculties after the development of the different races; and he did not dispute the nearly universal view among European anthropologists of the time that Europeans were intellectually superior to other races.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Charles Lyell wrote to Wallace praising the paper and saying that it had made a major contribution to resolving the dispute between monogenists and polygenists.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At about the same time, he began to maintain that natural selection could not account for mathematical, artistic, or musical genius, metaphysical musings, or wit and humour.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He stated that something in "the unseen universe of Spirit" had interceded at least three times in history: the creation of life from inorganic matter; the introduction of consciousness in the higher animals; and the generation of the higher mental faculties in humankind.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He believed that the raison d'être of the universe was the development of the human spirit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Reaction to Wallace's ideas on this topic among leading naturalists at the time varied.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Lyell endorsed Wallace's views on human evolution rather than Darwin's.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's belief that human consciousness could not be entirely a product of purely material causes was shared by a number of prominent intellectuals in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] All the same, many, including Huxley, Hooker, and Darwin himself, were critical of Wallace's views.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] As the historian of science and sceptic Michael Shermer has stated, Wallace's views in this area were at odds with two major tenets of the emerging Darwinian philosophy.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These were that evolution was not teleological (purpose-driven), and that it was not anthropocentric (human-centred).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Much later in his life Wallace returned to these themes, that evolution suggested that the universe might have a purpose, and that certain aspects of living organisms might not be explainable in terms of purely materialistic processes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He set out his ideas in a 1909 magazine article entitled *The World of Life*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace anticipated ideas about design in nature and directed evolution that would arise from religious traditions throughout the 20th century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In many accounts of the development of evolutionary theory, Wallace is mentioned only in passing as simply being the stimulus to the publication of Darwin's own theory.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In reality, Wallace developed his own distinct evolutionary views which diverged from Darwin's, and was considered by many (especially Darwin) to be a leading thinker on evolution in his day, whose ideas could not be ignored.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One historian of science has pointed out that, through both private correspondence and published works, Darwin and Wallace exchanged knowledge and stimulated each other's ideas and theories over an extended period.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace is the most-cited naturalist in Darwin's *Descent of Man*, occasionally in strong disagreement.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Darwin and Wallace agreed on the importance of natural selection, and some of the factors responsible for it: competition between species and geographical isolation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] But Wallace believed that evolution had a purpose ("teleology") in maintaining species' fitness to their environment, whereas Darwin hesitated to attribute any purpose to a random natural process.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Scientific discoveries since the 19th century support Darwin's viewpoint, by identifying additional mechanisms and triggers such as mutations triggered by environmental radiation or mutagenic chemicals.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace remained an ardent defender of natural selection for the rest of his life.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] By the 1880s, evolution was widely accepted in scientific circles, but natural selection less so.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's 1889 *Darwinism* was a response to the scientific critics of natural selection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Of all Wallace's books, it is the most cited by scholarly publications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1872, at the urging of many of his friends, including Darwin, Philip Sclater, and Alfred Newton, Wallace began research for a general review of the geographic distribution of animals.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Initial progress was slow, in part because classification systems for many types of animals were in flux.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He resumed the work in earnest in 1874 after the publication of a number of new works on classification.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Extending the system developed by Sclater for birds—which divided the earth into six separate geographic regions for describing species distribution—to cover mammals, reptiles and insects as well, Wallace created the basis for the zoogeographic regions in use today.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He discussed the factors then known to influence the current and past geographic distribution of animals within each geographic region.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] These factors included the effects of the appearance and disappearance of land bridges (such as the one currently connecting North America and South America) and the effects of periods of increased glaciation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When the Isthmus of Panama formed, species crossed it in both directions in the Great American Interchange.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He provided maps showing factors, such as elevation of mountains, depths of oceans, and the character of regional vegetation, that affected the distribution of animals.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He summarised all the known families and genera of the higher animals and listed their known geographic distributions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The text was organised so that it would be easy for a traveller to learn what animals could be found in a particular location.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The resulting two-volume work, *The Geographical Distribution of Animals*, was published in 1876 and served as the definitive text on zoogeography for the next 80 years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The book included evidence from the fossil record to discuss the processes of evolution and migration that had led to the geographical distribution of modern species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was very aware of, and interested in, the mass extinction of megafauna in the late Pleistocene.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *The Geographical Distribution of Animals* (1876) he wrote, "We live in a zoologically impoverished world, from which all the hugest, and fiercest, and strangest forms have recently disappeared".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He added that he believed the most likely cause for the rapid extinctions was glaciation, but by the time he wrote *World of Life* (1911) he had come to believe those extinctions were "due to man's agency".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1880, Wallace published the book *Island Life* as a sequel to *The Geographical Distribution of Animals*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It surveyed the distribution of both animal and plant species on islands.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace classified islands into oceanic and two types of continental islands.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Oceanic islands, in his view, such as the Galápagos and Hawaiian Islands (then called Sandwich Islands) formed in mid-ocean and never part of any large continent.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Such islands were characterised by a complete lack of terrestrial mammals and amphibians, and their inhabitants (except migratory birds and species introduced by humans) were typically the result of accidental colonisation and subsequent evolution.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Continental islands, in his scheme, were divided into those that were recently separated from a continent (like Britain) and those much less recently (like Madagascar).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace discussed how that difference affected flora and fauna.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He discussed how isolation affected evolution and how that could result in the preservation of classes of animals, such as the lemurs of Madagascar that were remnants of once widespread continental faunas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He extensively discussed how changes of climate, particularly periods of increased glaciation, may have affected the distribution of flora and fauna on some islands, and the first portion of the book discusses possible causes of these great ice ages.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] *Island Life* was considered a very important work at the time of its publication.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It was discussed extensively in scientific circles both in published reviews and in private correspondence.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's extensive work in biogeography made him aware of the impact of human activities on the natural world.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was also impressed by George Perkins Marsh's influential book Man and Nature.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *Tropical Nature and Other Essays* (1878), citing Marsh, he warned about the dangers of deforestation and soil erosion, especially in tropical climates prone to heavy rainfall.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Noting the complex interactions between vegetation and climate, he warned that the extensive clearing of rainforest for coffee cultivation in Ceylon (now called Sri Lanka) and India would adversely impact the climate in those countries and lead to their impoverishment due to soil erosion.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In *Island Life*, Wallace again mentioned deforestation and invasive species.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On the impact of European colonisation on the island of Saint Helena, he wrote that the island was "now so barren and forbidding that some persons find it difficult to believe that it was once all green and fertile".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He explained that the soil was protected by the island's vegetation; once that was destroyed, the soil was washed off the steep slopes by heavy tropical rain, leaving "bare rock or sterile clay".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He attributed the "irreparable destruction" to feral goats, introduced in 1513.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The island's forests were further damaged by the "reckless waste" of the East India Company from 1651, which used the bark of valuable redwood and ebony trees for tanning, leaving the wood to rot unused.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's comments on environment grew more urgent later in his career.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He concluded that the Earth was the only planet in the Solar System that could possibly support life, mainly because it was the only one in which water could exist in the liquid phase.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His treatment of Mars in this book was brief, and in 1907, Wallace returned to the subject with the book *Is Mars Habitable?* to criticise the claims made by the American astronomer Percival Lowell that there were Martian canals built by intelligent beings.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace did months of research, consulted various experts, and produced his own scientific analysis of the Martian climate and atmospheric conditions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Richard Milner comments that Wallace "effectively debunked Lowell's illusionary network of Martian canals." Wallace became interested in the topic because his anthropocentric philosophy inclined him to believe that man would be unique in the universe.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was an enthusiast of phrenology.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Early in his career, he experimented with hypnosis, then known as mesmerism, managing to hypnotise some of his students in Leicester.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When he began these experiments, the topic was very controversial: early experimenters, such as John Elliotson, had been harshly criticised by the medical and scientific establishment.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace drew a connection between his experiences with mesmerism and spiritualism, arguing that one should not deny observations on "a priori grounds of absurdity or impossibility".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace began investigating spiritualism in the summer of 1865, possibly at the urging of his older sister Fanny Sims.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] After reviewing the literature and attempting to test what he witnessed at séances, he came to believe in it.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For the rest of his life, he remained convinced that at least some séance phenomena were genuine, despite accusations of fraud and evidence of trickery.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] One biographer suggested that the emotional shock when his first fiancée broke their engagement contributed to his receptiveness to spiritualism.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Other scholars have emphasised his desire to find scientific explanations for all phenomena.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1874, Wallace visited the spirit photographer Frederick Hudson.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He declared that a photograph of him with his deceased mother was genuine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others reached a different conclusion: Hudson's photographs had previously been exposed as fraudulent in 1872.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's public advocacy of spiritualism and his repeated defence of spiritualist mediums against allegations of fraud in the 1870s damaged his scientific reputation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1875 he published the evidence he believed proved his position in *On Miracles and Modern Spiritualism*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] His attitude permanently strained his relationships with previously friendly scientists such as Henry Bates, Thomas Huxley, and even Darwin.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Others, such as the physiologist William Benjamin Carpenter and zoologist E.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Ray Lankester became publicly hostile to Wallace over the issue.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace was heavily criticised by the press; *The Lancet* was particularly harsh.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] This he is said to have done in an underhanded manner, and I well remember the indignation it gave rise to in the B.A.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Council." Hooker eventually relented and agreed to support the pension request.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1870, a flat-Earth proponent named John Hampden offered a £500 wager (roughly equivalent to £51,000 in 2025) in a magazine advertisement to anyone who could demonstrate a convex curvature in a body of water such as a river, canal, or lake.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace, intrigued by the challenge and short of money at the time, designed an experiment in which he set up two objects along a six-mile (10 km) stretch of canal.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Both objects were at the same height above the water, and he mounted a telescope on a bridge at the same height above the water as well.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] When seen through the telescope, one object appeared higher than the other, showing the curvature of the Earth.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The judge for the wager, the editor of *Field* magazine, declared Wallace the winner, but Hampden refused to accept the result.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He sued Wallace and launched a campaign, which persisted for several years, of writing letters to various publications and to organisations of which Wallace was a member denouncing him as a swindler and a thief.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace won multiple libel suits against Hampden, but the resulting litigation cost Wallace more than the amount of the wager, and the controversy frustrated him for years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In the early 1880s, Wallace joined the debate over mandatory smallpox vaccination.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace originally saw the issue as a matter of personal liberty; but, after studying statistics provided by anti-vaccination activists, he began to question the efficacy of vaccination.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] At the time, the germ theory of disease was new and far from universally accepted.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Moreover, no one knew enough about the human immune system to understand why vaccination worked.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace discovered instances where supporters of vaccination had used questionable, in a few cases completely false, statistics to support their arguments.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Always suspicious of authority, Wallace suspected that physicians had a vested interest in promoting vaccination, and became convinced that reductions in the incidence of smallpox that had been attributed to vaccination were due to better hygiene and improvements in public sanitation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Another factor in Wallace's thinking was his belief that, because of the action of natural selection, organisms were in a state of balance with their environment, and that everything in nature, served a useful purpose.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace pointed out that vaccination, which at the time was often unsanitary, could be dangerous.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1890, Wallace gave evidence to a royal commission investigating the controversy.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It found errors in his testimony, including some questionable statistics.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] *The Lancet* averred that Wallace and other activists were being selective in their choice of statistics.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The commission found that smallpox vaccination was effective and should remain compulsory, though they recommended some changes in procedures to improve safety, and that the penalties for people who refused to comply be made less severe.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Years later, in 1898, Wallace wrote a pamphlet, *Vaccination a Delusion; Its Penal Enforcement a Crime*, attacking the commission's findings.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It, in turn, was attacked by *The Lancet*, which stated that it repeated many of the same errors as his evidence given to the commission.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] As a result of his writing, Wallace became a well-known figure both as a scientist and as a social activist, and was often sought out for his views.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He became president of the anthropology section of the British Association in 1866, and of the Entomological Society of London in 1870.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1873.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The British Association elected him as head of its biology section in 1876.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was elected to the Royal Society in 1893.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He was asked to chair the International Congress of Spiritualists meeting in London in 1898.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He received honorary doctorates and professional honours, such the Royal Society's Royal Medal in 1868 and its Darwin Medal in 1890, and the Order of Merit in 1908.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace's fame faded quickly after his death.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] For a long time, he was treated as a relatively obscure figure in the history of science.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Reasons for this lack of attention may have included his modesty, his willingness to champion unpopular causes without regard for his own reputation, and the discomfort of much of the scientific community with some of his unconventional ideas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The reason that the theory of evolution is popularly credited to Darwin is likely the impact of Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Recently, Wallace has become better known, with the publication of at least five book-length biographies and two anthologies of his writings published since 2000.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A web page dedicated to Wallace scholarship is maintained at Western Kentucky University.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A collection of his medals, including the Order of Merit, were sold at auction for £273,000 in 2022.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Natural History Museum, London, co-ordinated commemorative events for the Wallace centenary worldwide in the 'Wallace100' project in 2013.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On 24 January, his portrait was unveiled in the Main Hall of the museum by Bill Bailey, a fervent admirer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Bailey further championed Wallace in his 2013 BBC Two series "Bill Bailey's Jungle Hero".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] On 7 November 2013, the 100th anniversary of Wallace's death, Sir David Attenborough unveiled a statue of Wallace at the museum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The statue, sculpted by Anthony Smith, was donated by the A.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] It depicts Wallace as a young man, collecting in the jungle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] November 2013 marked the debut of *The Animated Life of A.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Wallace*, a paper-puppet animation film dedicated to Wallace's centennial.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In addition, Bailey unveiled a bust of Wallace, sculpted by Felicity Crawley, in Twyn Square in Usk, Monmouthshire in November 2021.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Commemorations of the 200th anniversary of Wallace's birth celebrated during the course of 2023 range from naturalist walk events to scientific congresses and presentations.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A Harvard Museum of Natural History event in April 2023 will also include a mixologist-designed special cocktail to honor Wallace's legacy.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Mount Wallace in California's Sierra Nevada mountain range was named in his honour in 1895.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1928, a house at Richard Hale School (then called Hertford Grammar School, where he had been a pupil) was named after Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Alfred Russel Wallace building is a prominent feature of the Glyntaff campus at the University of South Wales, by Pontypridd, with several teaching spaces and laboratories for science courses.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The Natural Sciences Building at Swansea University and lecture theatre at Cardiff University are named after him, as are impact craters on Mars and the Moon.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 1986, the Royal Entomological Society mounted a year-long expedition to the Dumoga-Bone National Park in North Sulawesi named Project Wallace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] A group of Indonesian islands is known as the Wallacea biogeographical region in his honour, and Operation Wallacea, named after the region, awards "Alfred Russel Wallace Grants" to undergraduate ecology students.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] Several hundred species of plants and animals, both living and fossil, have been named after Wallace, such as the gecko *Cyrtodactylus wallacei*, and the freshwater stingray *Potamotrygon wallacei*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] More recently, several new species have been named during the bicentenary year of Wallace's birth, including a large spider from Peru, *Linothele wallacei* Sherwood *et al*., 2023 and a South African weevil, *Nama wallacei* Meregalli & Borovec, 2023.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] In 2002, historian of science Michael Shermer published a quantitative analysis of Wallace's publications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He found that Wallace had published 22 full-length books and at least 747 shorter pieces, 508 of which were scientific papers (191 of them published in *Nature*).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] He further broke down the 747 short pieces by their primary subjects: 29% were on biogeography and natural history, 27% were on evolutionary theory, 25% were social commentary, 12% were on anthropology, and 7% were on spiritualism and phrenology.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] An online bibliography of Wallace's writings has more than 750 entries.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alfred-russel-wallace-p02] The standard author abbreviation Wallace is used to indicate this person as the author when citing a botanical name.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As the name implies, it is designed to handle a wider variety of terrain than most other vehicles.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It is street-legal in some countries, but not in most states, territories and provinces of Australia, the United States, and Canada.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] By the current ANSI definition, ATVs are intended for use by a single operator, but some ATVs, referred to as tandem ATVs, have been developed for use by the driver and one passenger.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The rider sits on and operates these vehicles like a motorcycle, but the extra wheels give more stability at slower speeds.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Although most are equipped with three or four wheels, six or eight wheel (tracked) models exist and have existed historically for specialized applications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Multiple-user analogues with side-by-side seating are called utility terrain vehicles (UTVs) or side-by-sides to distinguish the classes of vehicle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Both classes tend to have similar powertrain parts.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Engine sizes of ATVs for sale in the United States as of 2008 ranged from 49 to 1,000 cc (3.0 to 61 cu in).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Royal Enfield built and sold the first powered four-wheeler in 1893.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It had many bicycle components, including handlebars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Royal Enfield resembles a modern ATV-style quad bike but was designed as a form of horseless carriage for road use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] With the introduction of straddle ridden ATVs, the term AATV was introduced to define the original amphibious ATV category.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The first three-wheeled ATV was the Sperry-Rand Tricart.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It was designed in 1967 as a graduate project of John Plessinger at the Cranbrook Academy of Arts near Detroit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Tricart was straddle-ridden with a sit-in rather than sit-on style (similar to the contemporaneous Big Wheel toy).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1968 Plessinger sold the Tricart patents and design rights to Sperry-Rand New Holland who manufactured them commercially.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Numerous small American manufacturers of 3-wheelers followed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] These small manufacturers were unable to compete when larger motorcycle companies like Honda entered the market in 1969.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda introduced their first sit-on straddle-ridden three-wheeled all-terrain vehicle in 1969, known as a US90, as a 1970 Model.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Variations would be popularized in the James Bond movie, *Diamonds Are Forever* and TV shows such as *Doctor Who*, *Magnum, P.I.* and *Hart to Hart*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1973, Honda trademarked the term "**All Terrain Cycle**" (ATC), applying it to all Honda's three-wheeled ATVs; it became a universal name associated with all vehicles of this type.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It was directly influenced by earlier 6-wheeled AATVs of the sixties, and utilized balloon tires for both a low environmental impact and to compensate for a lack of mechanical suspension.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda entered the 1980s with a virtual monopoly in the market, due to effective patents on design and engine placement.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] By 1980, other companies paid patent royalties to Honda to enter the lucrative ATC field with their own machines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Yamaha introduced their first ATC, the Tri-Moto YZ125.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Kawasaki followed suit the next year with the KLT200, while Suzuki produced their first model, the ALT125, in 1982.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As the popularity of ATCs increased dramatically, rapid development ensued.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The ability to go anywhere on terrain that most other vehicles could not cross soon made them popular with US and Canadian hunters.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As other manufacturers were entering the market, Honda was diversifying, offering the ATC250R, the first Sport ATC intended for competition, in 1981.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The 1982 Honda ATC200E Big Red was a landmark model.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It featured both suspension and racks, making it the first ATC designed specifically for utility, and would become the world's best-selling ATC.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda followed that effort in 1983 with the ATC200X, an easy-to-handle 192 cc (0.192 L; 11.7 cu in) four-stroke Sport ATC that was ideal for new riders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Not to be outdone, Kawasaki and Yamaha responded with their own Sport ATCs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] 1984 saw the release of the Kawasaki KXT250 Tecate, and Yamaha followed in 1985 with the Tri-Z 250.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Both were liquid cooled 250 cc two-strokes capable of giving the Honda ATC250R competition.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In response to growing market, American Specialty manufacturer Tiger also introduced a series of ATCs, hand-built-to-order models that included the Tiger 500, the largest displacement ATC produced commercially.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While Kawasaki and Yamaha both produced utility ATCs, famously making the KLT 250 Police and Yamahauler respectively, Suzuki turned their attention to building Sport Quads.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda continued to diversify their line-up (at peak offering 10 distinct models), releasing the larger, fully suspended 250 cc Big Red utility ATC, and introduced the 350X Sport ATC, their largest displacement machine, in 1985.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] But the bulk of their sales were the 200cc line, offering six models and selling over 500,000 units in 3 years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda's response to the Tecate and Tri-Z, the liquid cooled 1985 and 1986 ATC250R, remains one of the most desirable ATCs of the era, and aftermarket support still follows the machine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] American-based manufacturers also produced ATCs in this period, albeit in small numbers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Polaris offered the Scrambler in 1985 and 1986, producing appx 1600 units.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Speciality manufacturer Tiger ATV also produced a range of ATCs, but their liquidation in 1991 left no official record of how many units were produced.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The collector ATV market estimates vary drastically, from 300 to as many as 1000 units total production.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Tiger ATCs were offered for three years, with models using 80 to 500 cc (0.0800 to 0.500 L; 4.88 to 30.5 cu in) two-stroke engines provided by KTM and Rotax.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Tiger 500 is notable for being the fastest consumer ATC available, with tested top speeds of +80 mph from the stock 42 horsepower (31.3 kW)@6500rpm engine and 5 speed gearbox.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] With final drive gearing changes, the ATC could exceed 100 mph.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] However, due to the rarity of the machines the brand never became well-known, and as all Tiger Models were custom-ordered and built to the buyer's specifications for the purpose of factory ATV racing, Polaris is generally known as the first American 'Production' ATV producer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Production of three-wheelers was voluntarily ceased by all manufacturers by 1987, in light of safety concerns, and ahead of any legislation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Though later studies showed that three-wheelers were not considered more unstable than four-wheelers (although accidents are equally severe in both classes), manufacturers agreed to a 10-year moratorium on production, and to collectively financing a +US$100 million ATV safety campaign.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Despite the moratorium lifting, manufacturers did not return to the ATC market, focusing instead on four-wheeled ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A ban on sales of new or used three-wheelers and a recall of all remaining three-wheelers was proposed by the American Academy of Pediatrics.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] These safety issues with three-wheel ATCs caused a shift in the buying public, as the sales of later four-wheel ATV models grew rapidly.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While three-wheel models ended production in 1987, agreements between the major manufacturers and the US U.S.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Consumer Product Safety Commission to officially cease production and finance safety campaigns moved forward.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While the lighter weight of ATCs made them popular with certain riders, manufacturers continued to focus on ATV production.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] US Public Law 110-314, enacted on August 8, 2008, separated ATCs from existing new production ATV safety standards, and requires new standards for three-wheeled ATCs to be drafted.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This effectively suspended importation of three-wheeled ATCs, until new standards of safety can be drafted.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As of 2020, such standards have not been drafted.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While search engines can find informal information suggesting major Japanese manufacturers pressed for this measure due to an influx of inexpensive Chinese ATCs in the American market, no official documentation or cited sources support these claims.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Currently, all manufacturers not based in the US are restricted from the manufacture and sale of new Three-Wheeled All Terrain Cycles, until safety standards can be implemented.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Below is a summary of Section 232, which effects the ATC ban.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki was a leader in the development of mass production four-wheeled ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It sold the first model, the 1982 QuadRunner LT125, which was a recreational machine for beginners.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Adventure Vehicles of Monroe, Louisiana made the first quad ATV in 1980.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It was a rudimentary vehicle reminiscent of the Tote Gote of the 1960s.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki sold the first four-wheeled mini ATV, the LT50, from 1984 to 1987.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] After the LT50, Suzuki sold the first ATV with a CVT transmission, the LT80, from 1987 to 2006.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1985 Suzuki introduced to the industry the first high-performance four-wheel ATV, the Suzuki LT250R QuadRacer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This machine was in production for the 1985–1992 model years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] During its production run, it underwent three major engineering makeovers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] However, the core features were retained.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] These were: a sophisticated long-travel suspension, a liquid-cooled, two-stroke motor, and a fully-manual five-speed transmission (for 1985–1986 models), and a six-speed transmission (for the '87–'92 models).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It was a machine exclusively designed for racing by highly skilled riders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Honda responded a year later with the FourTrax TRX250R—a machine that has not been replicated until recently.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It currently remains a trophy winner and competitor to big-bore ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Kawasaki responded with its Tecate-4 250.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The TRX250R was very similar to the ATC250R it eventually replaced and is often considered one of the greatest sport ATVs ever built.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1987, Yamaha Motor Company introduced a different type of high-performance machine, the Banshee 350, which featured a twin-cylinder liquid-cooled two-stroke motor from the RD350LC street motorcycle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Heavier and more difficult to ride in the dirt than the 250s, the Banshee became a popular machine with sand dune riders thanks to its unique power delivery.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Banshee remains popular, but 2006 is the last year it was available in the U.S.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] (due to EPA emissions regulations); it remained available in Canada until 2008 and in Australia until 2012.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Warrior 350 was introduced in 1987 and went on for years as a light and fast ATV.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Shortly after the introduction of the Banshee in 1987, Suzuki released the LT500R QuadRacer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This unique quad was powered by a 500 cc liquid-cooled two-stroke engine with a five-speed transmission.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This ATV earned the nickname "Quadzilla" with its remarkable amount of speed and size.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While there are claims of 100+ mph (160 km/h) stock Quadzillas, it was officially recorded by 3&4 Wheel Action magazine as reaching a top speed of over 79 mph (127 km/h) in a high-speed shootout in its 1988 June issue, making it the fastest production four-wheeled ATV ever produced.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Suzuki discontinued the production of the LT500R in 1990 after just four years.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] At the same time, the development of utility ATVs was rapidly escalating.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The 1986 Honda FourTrax TRX350 4x4 ushered in the era of four-wheel-drive ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Other manufacturers quickly followed suit, and 4x4s have remained the most popular type of ATV ever since.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] These machines are popular with hunters, farmers, ranchers, and workers at construction sites.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Models are divided into the sport and utility markets.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport models are generally small, light, two-wheel-drive vehicles that accelerate quickly, have a manual transmission, and run at speeds up to approximately 80 mph (130 km/h).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Utility models are generally bigger four-wheel-drive vehicles with a maximum speed of up to approximately 70 mph (110 km/h).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] They can haul small loads on attached racks or small dump beds, and tow small trailers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Due to the different weights, each has advantages on different types of terrain.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A popular model is Yamaha's Raptor 700, which has a nearly 700 cc four-stroke engine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Six-wheel models often have a small dump bed, with an extra set of wheels at the back to increase the payload capacity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] They can be either four-wheel-drive (back wheels driving only), or six-wheel-drive.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2011 LandFighter was founded, "the first Dutch/European ATV brand".
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Most production is in Taiwan, to European standards; the ATVs are finally assembled in the Netherlands.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety helmets, mandatory in some jurisdictions, provide the rider with some protection in the case of an accident.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety courses and educational literature reduced the number and severity of accidents among ATC and ATV riders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As cornering is more challenging on a three-wheel ATC than with a four-wheeled machine, properly leaning into the turn is required to counterbalance the weight and keep the machine stable.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Careless operators may roll over at high speeds.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The lighter front-end and smaller footprint of ATCs present both a flipping and steering hazard under acceleration and on inclines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Lateral rollovers may also occur when traversing steep inclines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Four-wheel quad cycles have a tendency to roll over, often injuring or killing the rider.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Suitably designed roll bars can be fitted, which do not prevent the cycle from overturning, but prop it up, providing some protection for the rider.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Safety has been a major issue with ATVs due to the many deaths and injuries associated with them and the lack of protection due to the absence of a rigid cab.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Modern ATVs were introduced in the early 1970s, with almost immediate alarming injury rates for children and adolescents.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Based on analysis of the National Trauma Data Bank, ATVs are more dangerous than dirt bikes, possibly due to crush injuries and failure to wear safety gear such as helmets.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] They are as dangerous as motorcycles, based on mortality and injury scores.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] More children and women, who are less likely to wear helmets, are injured on ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Many common injuries can be prevented with the use of proper protective equipment.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Most ATV manufacturers recommend at least a suitable DOT-approved helmet, protective eyewear, gloves and suitable riding boots for all riding conditions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport or aggressive riders, or riders on challenging terrain (such as those rock crawling or hillclimbing), may opt for a motocross-style chest protector and knee/shin guards for further protection.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Use of tires suited to a particular terrain can also play a vital role in preventing injuries.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Fatal accidents typically occur when the vehicle rolls over.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Wearing a helmet can reduce the risk of death by 42% and the risk of nonfatal head injury by 64%.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] From 2016 to 2018, 1591 people died in ATV-associated incidents, with 28% involving children and youth under age 25.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Focus has shifted to machine size balanced with the usage of ATVs categorized by age ranges and engine displacements—in line with the consent decrees.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs are mandated to bear a label from the manufacturer stating that the use of machines greater than 90 cc by riders under the age of 12 is prohibited.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This is a 'manufacturer/CPSC recommendation' and not necessarily state law.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Although youth-sized ATVs are designed and available for younger riders, there are serious concerns regarding their appropriateness and safety for youth.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The American Academy of Pediatrics and the CPSC recommended that children under the age of 16 should not ride ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In the United States, about 40,000 children under age 16 are treated in emergency departments for ATV-related injuries each year.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A Canadian study stated that "associated injury patterns, severity, and costs to the healthcare system" of pediatric injuries associated to ATVs resemble those caused by motor vehicles, and that public policies should reflect this.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Helmets are underutilized and result in Glasgow Coma Scale scores in children presenting from ATV accidents being similar to those in motorcycle accidents.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The Consumer Product Safety Commission met in March 2005 to discuss the dangers of ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Data from 2004 showed 44,000 injuries and almost 150 fatalities in children while riding ATVs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In response to calls for further regulation, the CPSC's director of compliance, John Gibson Mullan, said that because the statistics were not rising, existing measures were working.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] *The New York Times* reported an accusation from a staff member that Mullan, who had previously worked as a lawyer for the ATV industry, had distorted the statistics and prevented further debate.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 1988, the All-terrain Vehicle Safety Institute (ASI) was formed to provide training and education for ATV riders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The cost of attending the training is minimal and is free for purchasers of new machines that fall within the correct age and size guidelines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Successful completion of a safety training class is, in many states, a minimum requirement for minors to be granted permission to ride on public land.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Some states have had to implement their own safety training programs, as the ASI program cannot include those riders with ATVs outside of the age and size guidelines, which may still fall within the states' laws.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] From January 1, 2019, the United States Consumer Product Safety Commission updated ATV lighting requirements, requiring all categories of ATVs to be equipped with a stop lamp and side reflectors similar to those required on passenger cars.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In industry, agriculture workers are disproportionately at risk for ATV accidents.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Most fatalities occur in white men over the age of 55.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATV's have the ability to be officially street legal and can be used on at least certain roads in 21 states, requirements vary by state however.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A "quad" is recognised by UK law as a vehicle with four wheels and a mass of less than 550 kg (1,210 lb).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A quad cycle to be used on a public road in the UK must be taxed, insured and registered, and the driver must have a category B (car) or B1 (motor vehicles with 4 wheels up to 400 kg unladen or 550 kg if designed for carrying goods) licence.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In the United Kingdom, the safety issues of cars classed as quad cycles are illustrated by the case of the G-Wiz (REVAi).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The electric microcar was given a Euro NCAP specification test, and the results showed that the vehicle's occupants would suffer "serious or life-threatening" injuries in a 64 km/h (40 mph) crash.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The UK Department for Transport concluded that there were serious safety concerns when the REVA was crashed at 35 mph (56 km/h).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] After consultation with stakeholders including farmers and quad cycle manufacturers, Australia's Heads of Workplace Safety Authorities (HWSA) in 2011 released a strategy intended to reduce the number of deaths and serious injuries associated with quad-bike use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The development of the report was closely followed by *The Weekly Times* newspaper and ABC television which reviewed the issue through its *7.30* program.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] When the report was released the only model of anti-crush protection on the market was the Australian-made "Quadbar", which was vigorously opposed by the industry through media activity and a poster campaign at regional events for farmers which are often used to showcase new products.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The industry argued that the device had not been properly tested and that past studies of tractor-style ROPS such as a full-frame 'cage' around the operator were not only ineffective, but could add to the risk to injury or death.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In February 2012, the Melbourne-based Institute for Safety, Compensation and Recovery Research (ISCRR) published a paper which criticised the research claims of the manufacturers in relation to crush protection devices.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The paper reviewed research in a number of countries since 1993 in relation to rollover protection and found that the industry's opposition to rollover protection could not be supported because of limitations in past research.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] It recommended further research on the topic and the development of research tools based on the use of ATV/quadbikes in Australian conditions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In most provinces, ATV users are required to register their vehicle and have a designated off-highway license plate.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Some provinces, like Nova Scotia, recently moved to allow ATVs limited road shoulder usage for the purpose of travelling from one trailhead to another.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In Germany the legal situation is very unrestrictive, but complex.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Almost, if not any manufacturer ATV registered at the KBA (Kraftfahrtbundesamt) can be registered for road use in Germany.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Vehicle-taxes, insurance and a number plate as well as a MOT (TÜV) are required.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Quads can be accredited in two different ways in Germany.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Usually they are taxed and insured as a regular automobile, which results in the tax being calculated by emissions and displacement in 100ccm steps.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs registered as an automobile have to be restricted to a power output of 20 hp/15 kW and are allowed to be driven with a passenger, provided a passenger seat is registered in the vehicle papers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The quad must have at least one rear mirror on the left side, minimum 10x5cm.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The vehicle must have a high-/low-beam headlight, brake light, indicators, a number plate mount on front and back, and a horn.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs under 400 kilograms (880 lb) do not need a reverse gear.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Over 400 kilograms (880 lb) empty weight, a reverse gear and reverse light are required.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The maximum engine noise restrictions depend on date of first registration and engine displacement.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] On the other hand, ATVs can be registered "as agricultural and silvicultural" (LoF/Land- oder Forstwirtschaftlich) giving the owner some benefits: The quad can be driven with power outputs more than 20 hp and tax is much cheaper, being calculated by empty weight.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The insurance cost is much lower than for other agricultural vehicles and ATVs,.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Custom builds and engine replacements are possible to get street legal, by undergoing a single-acceptance procedure from the MOT(TÜV).
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This results in some custom quads popularly sporting 4-cycle motorcycle engines street legal.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] A common example are Yamaha Raptor 700 Conversions to a Yamaha 1000 cc engine from the early Yamaha Fazer and R1.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVS are mostly treated as a regular automobile in Germany, which means no special-vehicle or motorcycle licence is needed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The regular driving license class B (multiple track motorised vehicles up to 3.5 tons) is sufficient even for LoF registered vehicles.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Consequently, until 2013, quads could be driven only by people at least 18 years old with a drivers license.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] People under 18 may have a 50 cc or 125 cc bike license, but this does not allow them to drive quad bikes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As quad bikes were treated as automobiles, wearing a helmet was not required until January 2006, when helmets became required for ATVs, three-wheelers, trikes, etc.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] No additional protective gear is required.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Officially, driving a quad requires the owner to always carry a hazard triangle and a first-aid kit, and a reflective vest if the quad is registered as an agricultural vehicle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Due to the lack of storage room, police usually don't check the back of the vehicle, but if they lack the required equipment, they may be prosecuted.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs accounted for 58% of the SI (spark ignited) recreational vehicles in the US in the year 2000.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] That year, recreational SI vehicles produced 0.16% of NOx, 8% of HC, 5% of CO and 0.8% of PM emissions for all vehicles, both highway and nonroad.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] As a point of comparison, the nonroad SI < 19 kW (~25 hp) category (small spark ignition engines such as lawnmowers) comprised 20% of HC and 23% of CO total emissions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While recreational SI vehicles produce an aggregate of <4% of all HC emissions in the US, based on the relatively small population of ATVs (<1.2M) and small annual usage (<350 hrs), EPA emission regulations now include such engines, starting with the model year 2006.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Engines meeting these standards now produce only 3% of the HC emissions that previously unregulated engines did.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] While the deep treads on some ATV tires are effective for navigating rocky, muddy and root covered terrain, these treads are also capable of digging channels that may drain bogs, increase sedimentation in streams at crossings and damage groomed snowmobile trails.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Proper trail construction techniques can mitigate these effects.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In some countries where fencing is not common, such as the US, Canada and Australia, some ATV riders knowingly cross privately owned property in rural areas and travel over public or private properties, although only permitted on trails.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Subsequently, environmentalists criticize ATV riding as a sport for excessive use in areas which biologists consider to be sensitive, especially wetlands and sand dunes and in much of inland Australia.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Because both scientific studies and U.S.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] National Forest Service personnel have identified unregulated Off-Road Vehicles (ORVs) as the source of major detrimental impacts on national forests, the U.S.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Forest Service is currently engaged in the Travel Management Process, wherein individual forests are restricting all off-road motorized travel to approved trails and roads.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] This is in contrast to its previously allowed, unregulated cross-country travel across all national forest lands, except for specifically designated wilderness areas.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs using tracks instead of wheels are used at France's Cap Prudhomme in Antarctica.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVs are also used in agriculture to bridge the advantages of trucks and tractors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] They are used in a variety of industries for their maneuverability and off-roading ability.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Sport models are built with performance, rather than utility, in mind.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] To be successful at fast trail riding, an ATV must have light weight, high power, good suspension and a low center of gravity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] These machines can be modified for such racing disciplines as motocross, woods racing (also known as cross country), desert racing (also known as Hare Scrambles), hill climbing, ice racing, speedway, Tourist Trophy (TT), flat track, drag racing and others.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Throughout the United States and the United Kingdom there are many quad racing clubs with enduro and quadcross sections.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] GNCC Racing began around 1980 and includes hare scramble and enduro type races.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] To date, events are mainly held in the eastern part of the United States.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] GNCC racing features many types of obstacles such as, hill climbing, creek and log crossings, dirt roads and wooded trails.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATV National Motocross Championship was formed around 1985.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVMX events are hosted at premiere motocross racetracks throughout the United States.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] ATVMX consists of several groups, including the Pro (AMA Pro) and Amateur (ATVA) series.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Friday involves amateur practicing and racing on Saturday and Sunday.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Saturday also involves racing for the Pro Am Women and Pro Am Unlimited classes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Sunday involves racing for the Pro and Pro Am production ATVs, but are scored separately.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] On average weekend over 500 racers will compete.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The FIM organizes the Quadcross of Nations at the end of the year.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The competition involves teams of three riders representing their nations.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] There are three motos with two riders of each nation competing per moto.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The location of the event changes from year to year.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Championship Mud Racing/CMR saw its infancy in 2006 as leaders of the ATV industry recognized a need for uniformity of classes and rules of various local mud bog events.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Providing standardized rules created the need for a governing body that both racers and event promoters could turn to and CMR was born.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Once unified, a true points series was established and lead to a national championship for what was once nothing more than a hobby for most.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2007 the finalized board of directors was established and the first races were held in 2008.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Currently, the CMR schedule includes eight competition dates spanning from March to November.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Points are awarded throughout the season in several different competition classes of ATV and SxS Mud Racing.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The 2008 year included Mud Bog and Mudda-Cross competitions, but the 2009 and future seasons will only have Mudda-Cross competitions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Classes range from 0–499 cc to a Super-Modified class which will allow any size ATV in competition.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] In 2005 the FIM Cross-Country Rallies World Championship started with a Quad Championship and the Dakar Rally added the Quad category in 2008.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Because the 2008 Dakar Rally was cancelled, the 2009 Dakar Rally was the first Dakar Rally with Quads.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Amateur and professional three-wheeler racing across the United States has also spiked in popularity once again, at levels not seen since the factory teams raced in the 1980s.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Part of the appeal is the cheapness of parts, and how easy it is to get into.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Races are held at various local and large venues, particularly in Ohio, New York, Pennsylvania, Arizona, Michigan and California.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Payouts are sometimes awarded to winners.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Each year in June, the world's biggest three-wheeler gathering is held at Haspin Acres, in Laurel, Indiana, for the Trikefest event.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Over the course of 3 days complete with camping, hundreds of people gather for the event which features competitive racing such as MX style racing, drag racing, mud racing, hill climbs and other events.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] For those who wish not to compete, there are also many trails a person can ride. as many as 100 or more three-wheelers show up each year, some built and restored to be raffled off, others brought to ride.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The fastest speed recorded on a quad cycle, or ATV given a flying start, is 315.74 km/h (196.19 mph), by Terry Wilmeth (USA), at the Madras Airport in Madras, Oregon, USA, on 15 June 2008.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] The other major discovery was also made in 2021 by an Engineering student Mr.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] Sajith Sajeev Bindhu from UKF College of Engineering from India has been done, it was about the discovery of ATV rear suspension into A design and the research which helps to improve the stability of ATV into a better format.
[src:centrifugal-governor/all-terrain-vehicle] That was the latest major change that concluded in the era of ATV .
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:centrifugal-governor/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In optics, the **aperture** of an optical system (including a system consisting of a single lens) is the hole or opening that primarily limits light propagated through the system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The aperture defines a bundle of rays from each point on an object that will come to a focus in the image plane.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] An optical system typically has many structures that limit ray bundles (ray bundles are also known as *pencils* of light).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] These structures may be the edge of a lens or mirror, or a ring or other fixture that holds an optical element in place or may be a special element such as a diaphragm placed in the optical path to limit the light admitted by the system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] These structures are called *stops*, and the **aperture stop** is the stop that primarily determines the cone of rays that an optical system accepts (see entrance pupil).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] As a result, it also determines the ray cone angle and brightness at the image point (see exit pupil).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Optical systems are typically designed for a particular stop to be the aperture stop, but it is possible for different stops to serve as the aperture stop for objects at different distances.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Some rays from object points away from the optical axis may clip on surfaces other than the aperture stop.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The aperture stop is not necessarily the smallest stop in the system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Magnification and demagnification by lenses and other elements can cause a relatively large stop to be the aperture stop for the system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In some contexts, especially in photography and astronomy, *aperture* refers to the opening diameter of the aperture stop through which light can pass.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For example, in a telescope, the aperture stop is typically the edges of the objective lens or mirror (or of the mount that holds it).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] One then speaks of a telescope as having, for example, a 100-centimetre (39 in) aperture.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In astrophotography, the aperture may be given as a linear measure (for example, in inches or millimetres) or as the dimensionless ratio between that measure and the focal length.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In other photography, it is usually given as a ratio.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A usual expectation is that the term *aperture* refers to the opening of the aperture stop, but in reality, the term aperture and the aperture stop are mixed in use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Sometimes even stops that are not the aperture stop of an optical system are also called apertures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The word aperture is also used in other contexts to indicate a system which blocks off light outside a certain region.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In astronomy, for example, a photometric aperture around a star usually corresponds to a circular window around the image of a star within which the light intensity is assumed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The aperture stop is an important element in most optical designs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Its most obvious feature is that it limits the amount of light that can reach the image/film plane.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] This can be either unavoidable due to the practical limit of the aperture stop size, or deliberate to prevent saturation of a detector or overexposure of film.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In both cases, the size of the aperture stop determines the amount of light admitted by an optical system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In addition to an aperture stop, a photographic lens may have one or more *field stops*, which limit the system's field of view.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] When the field of view is limited by a field stop in the lens (rather than at the film or sensor) vignetting results; this is only a problem if the resulting field of view is less than was desired.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In astronomy, the opening diameter of the aperture stop (called the *aperture*) is a critical parameter in the design of a telescope.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Generally, one would want the *aperture* to be as large as possible, to collect the maximum amount of light from the distant objects being imaged.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The size of the aperture is limited, however, in practice by considerations of its manufacturing cost and time and its weight, as well as prevention of aberrations (as mentioned above).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Apertures are also used in laser energy control, close aperture z-scan technique, diffractions/patterns, and beam cleaning.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Laser applications include spatial filters, Q-switching, high intensity x-ray control.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In light microscopy, the word aperture may be used with reference to either the condenser (that changes the angle of light onto the specimen field), field iris (that changes the area of illumination on specimens) or possibly objective lens (forms primary images).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The aperture stop of a photographic lens can be adjusted to control the amount of light reaching the film or image sensor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In combination with variation of shutter speed, the aperture size will regulate the film's or image sensor's degree of exposure to light.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Typically, a fast shutter will require a larger aperture to ensure sufficient light exposure, and a slow shutter will require a smaller aperture to avoid excessive exposure.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A device called a diaphragm usually serves as the aperture stop and controls the aperture (the opening of the aperture stop).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The diaphragm functions much like the iris of the eye – it controls the effective diameter of the lens opening (called pupil in the eyes).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In general, the smaller the aperture (the larger the f-number), the greater the distance from the plane of focus the subject matter may be while still appearing in focus.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The lens aperture is usually specified as an f-number, the ratio of focal length to effective aperture diameter (the diameter of the entrance pupil).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A lens typically has a set of marked "f-stops" that the f-number can be set to.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A lower f-number denotes a greater aperture which allows more light to reach the film or image sensor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The photography term "one f-stop" refers to a factor of √2 (approx.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] 1.41) change in f-number which corresponds to a √2 change in aperture diameter, which in turn corresponds to a factor of 2 change in light intensity (by a factor 2 change in the aperture area).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Aperture priority is a semi-automatic shooting mode used in cameras.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] It permits the photographer to select an aperture setting and let the camera decide the shutter speed and sometimes also ISO sensitivity for the correct exposure.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] This is also referred to as Aperture Priority Auto Exposure, A mode, AV mode (aperture-value mode), or semi-auto mode.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] These are not sharp divisions, and ranges for specific lenses vary.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The specifications for a given lens typically include the maximum and minimum aperture (opening) sizes, for example, f/0.95 – f/22.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In this case, f/0.95 is currently the maximum aperture (the widest opening on a full-frame format for practical use), and f/22 is the minimum aperture (the smallest opening).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The maximum aperture tends to be of most interest and is always included when describing a lens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] This value is also known as the lens "speed", as it affects the exposure time.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Lenses with apertures opening f/2.8 or wider are referred to as "fast" lenses, although the specific point has changed over time (for example, in the early 20th century aperture openings wider than f/6 were considered fast.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The fastest lenses for the common 35 mm film format in general production have apertures of f/1.2 or f/1.4, with more at f/1.8 and f/2.0, and many at f/2.8 or slower; f/1.0 is unusual, though sees some use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] When comparing "fast" lenses, the image format used must be considered.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Lenses designed for a small format such as half frame or APS-C need to project a much smaller image circle than a lens used for large format photography.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Thus the optical elements built into the lens can be far smaller and cheaper.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In exceptional circumstances lenses can have even wider apertures with f-numbers smaller than 1.0; see lens speed: fast lenses for a detailed list.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For instance, both the current Leica Noctilux-M 50mm ASPH and a 1960s-era Canon 50mm rangefinder lens have a maximum aperture of f/0.95.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Cheaper alternatives began appearing in the early 2010s, such as the Cosina Voigtländer f/0.95 Nokton (several in the 10.5–60 mm range) and f/0.8 (29 mm) Super Nokton manual focus lenses in the Micro Four-Thirds System, and the Venus Optics (Laowa) Argus 35 mm f/0.95.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Professional lenses for some movie cameras have f-numbers as small as f/0.75.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Stanley Kubrick's film *Barry Lyndon* has scenes shot by candlelight with a NASA/Zeiss 50mm f/0.7, the fastest lens in film history.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Beyond the expense, these lenses have limited application due to the correspondingly shallower depth of field (DOF) – the scene must either be shallow, shot from a distance, or will be significantly defocused, though this may be the desired effect.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Zoom lenses typically have a maximum relative aperture (minimum f-number) of f/2.8 to f/6.3 through their range.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] High-end lenses will have a constant aperture, such as f/2.8 or f/4, which means that the relative aperture will stay the same throughout the zoom range.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A more typical consumer zoom will have a variable maximum relative aperture since it is harder and more expensive to keep the maximum relative aperture proportional to the focal length at long focal lengths; f/3.5 to f/5.6 is an example of a common variable aperture range in a consumer zoom lens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Accordingly, DSLR lens typically have minimum aperture of f/16, f/22, or f/32, while large format may go down to f/64, as reflected in the name of Group f/64.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Depth of field is a significant concern in macro photography, however, and there one sees smaller apertures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For example, the Canon MP-E 65mm can have effective aperture (due to magnification) as small as f/96.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The pinhole optic for Lensbaby creative lenses has an aperture of just f/177.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Where the two equivalent forms are related via the f-number *N = f* / *D*, with focal length *f* and entrance pupil diameter *D*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The focal length value is not required when comparing two lenses of the same focal length; a value of 1 can be used instead, and the other factors can be dropped as well, leaving area proportion to the reciprocal square of the f-number *N*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] If two cameras of different format sizes and focal lengths have the same angle of view, and the same aperture area, they gather the same amount of light from the scene.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In that case, the relative focal-plane illuminance, however, would depend only on the f-number *N*, so it is less in the camera with the larger format, longer focal length, and higher f-number.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] This assumes both lenses have identical transmissivity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Though as early as 1933 Torkel Korling had invented and patented for the Graflex large format reflex camera an automatic aperture control, not all early 35mm single lens reflex cameras had the feature.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] With a small aperture, this darkened the viewfinder, making viewing, focusing, and composition difficult.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Korling's design enabled full-aperture viewing for accurate focus, closing to the pre-selected aperture opening when the shutter was fired and simultaneously synchronising the firing of a flash unit.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The first SLR cameras with internal ("through-the-lens" or "TTL") meters (e.g., the Pentax Spotmatic) required that the lens be stopped down to the working aperture when taking a meter reading.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Subsequent models soon incorporated mechanical coupling between the lens and the camera body, indicating the working aperture to the camera for exposure while allowing the lens to be at its maximum aperture for composition and focusing; this feature became known as open-aperture metering.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For some lenses, including a few long telephotos, lenses mounted on bellows, and perspective-control and tilt/shift lenses, the mechanical linkage was impractical, and automatic aperture control was not provided.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Many such lenses incorporated a feature known as a "preset" aperture, which allows the lens to be set to working aperture and then quickly switched between working aperture and full aperture without looking at the aperture control.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] A typical operation might be to establish rough composition, set the working aperture for metering, return to full aperture for a final check of focus and composition, and focusing, and finally, return to working aperture just before exposure.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Although slightly easier than stopped-down metering, operation is less convenient than automatic operation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Preset aperture controls have taken several forms; the most common has been the use of essentially two lens aperture rings, with one ring setting the aperture and the other serving as a limit stop when switching to working aperture.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Examples of lenses with this type of preset aperture control are the Nikon PC Nikkor 28 mm f/3.5 and the SMC Pentax Shift 6×7 75 mm f/4.5.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The Nikon PC Micro-Nikkor 85 mm f/2.8D lens incorporates a mechanical pushbutton that sets working aperture when pressed and restores full aperture when pressed a second time.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Canon EF lenses, introduced in 1987, have electromagnetic diaphragms, eliminating the need for a mechanical linkage between the camera and the lens, and allowing automatic aperture control with the Canon TS-E tilt/shift lenses.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Nikon PC-E perspective-control lenses, introduced in 2008, also have electromagnetic diaphragms, a feature extended to their E-type range in 2013.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Optimal aperture depends both on optics (the depth of the scene versus diffraction), and on the performance of the lens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Optically, as a lens is stopped down, the defocus blur at the Depth of Field (DOF) limits decreases but diffraction blur increases.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] As a matter of performance, lenses often do not perform optimally when fully opened, and thus generally have better sharpness when stopped down some – this is sharpness in the plane of critical focus, setting aside issues of depth of field.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Beyond a certain point, there is no further sharpness benefit to stopping down, and the diffraction occurred at the edges of the aperture begins to become significant for imaging quality.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] There is accordingly a sweet spot, generally in the f/4 – f/8 range, depending on lens, where sharpness is optimal, though some lenses are designed to perform optimally when wide open.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] How significant this varies between lenses, and opinions differ on how much practical impact this has.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] But this may not be true if the final image is viewed under more demanding conditions, e.g., a very large final image viewed at normal distance, or a portion of an image enlarged to normal size (Hansma 1996).
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Hansma also suggests that the final-image size may not be known when a photograph is taken, and obtaining the maximum practicable sharpness allows the decision to make a large final image to be made at a later time; see also critical sharpness.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In many living optical systems, the eye consists of an iris which adjusts the size of the pupil, through which light enters.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The iris is analogous to the diaphragm, and the pupil (which is the adjustable opening in the iris) the aperture.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Refraction in the cornea causes the effective aperture (the entrance pupil in optics parlance) to differ slightly from the physical pupil diameter.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The entrance pupil is typically about 4 mm in diameter, although it can range from as narrow as 2 mm (f/8.3) in diameter in a brightly lit place to 8 mm (f/2.1) in the dark as part of adaptation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In rare cases, some individuals are able to dilate their pupils even beyond 8 mm (in scotopic lighting, close to the physical limit of the iris.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In humans, the average iris diameter is about 11.5 mm, which naturally influences the maximal size of the pupil as well, where larger iris diameters would typically have pupils which are able to dilate to a wider extreme than those with smaller irises.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Maximum dilated pupil size also decreases with age.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The iris controls the size of the pupil via two complementary sets muscles, the sphincter and dilator muscles, which are innervated by the parasympathetic and sympathetic nervous systems respectively, and act to induce pupillary constriction and dilation respectively.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The state of the pupil is closely influenced by various factors, primarily light (or absence of light), but also by emotional state, interest in the subject of attention, arousal, sexual stimulation, physical activity, accommodation state, and cognitive load.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The field of view is not affected by the size of the pupil.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Some individuals are also able to directly exert manual and conscious control over their iris muscles and hence are able to voluntarily constrict and dilate their pupils on command.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] However, this ability is rare and potential use or advantages are unclear.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] In digital photography, the 35mm-equivalent aperture range is sometimes considered to be more important than the actual f-number.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Equivalent aperture is the f-number adjusted to correspond to the f-number of the same size absolute aperture diameter on a lens with a 35mm equivalent focal length.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Smaller equivalent f-numbers are expected to lead to higher image quality based on more total light from the subject, as well as lead to reduced depth of field.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For example, a Sony Cyber-shot DSC-RX10 uses a 1" sensor, 24 – 200 mm with maximum aperture constant along the zoom range; f/2.8 has equivalent aperture range f/7.6, which is a lower equivalent f-number than some other f/2.8 cameras with smaller sensors.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] However, modern optical research concludes that sensor size does not actually play a part in the depth of field in an image.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] An aperture's f-number is not modified by the camera's sensor size because it is a ratio that only pertains to the attributes of the lens.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Instead, the higher crop factor that comes as a result of a smaller sensor size means that, in order to get an equal framing of the subject, the photo must be taken from further away, which results in a less blurry background, changing the perceived depth of field.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Similarly, a smaller sensor size with an equivalent aperture will result in a darker image because of the pixel density of smaller sensors with equivalent megapixels.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Every photosite on a camera's sensor requires a certain amount of surface area that is not sensitive to light, a factor that results in differences in pixel pitch and changes in the signal-noise ratio.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] However, neither the changed depth of field, nor the perceived change in light sensitivity are a result of the aperture.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Instead, equivalent aperture can be seen as a rule of thumb to judge how changes in sensor size might affect an image, even if qualities like pixel density and distance from the subject are the actual causes of changes in the image.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The terms *scanning aperture* and *sampling aperture* are often used to refer to the opening through which an image is sampled, or scanned, for example in a Drum scanner, an image sensor, or a television pickup apparatus.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The sampling aperture can be a literal optical aperture, that is, a small opening in space, or it can be a time-domain aperture for sampling a signal waveform.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] For example, film grain is quantified as *graininess* via a measurement of film density fluctuations as seen through a 0.048 mm sampling aperture.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] Aperture Science, a fictional company in the Portal fictional universe, is named after the optical system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/aperture] The company's logo heavily features an aperture, and has come to symbolize the series, fictional company, and the Aperture Science Computer-Aided Enrichment Center that the game series takes place in.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Woolf left Cornwall in 1785 to work for Joseph Bramah's engineering works in London.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] He worked there and at other firms as an engineer and engine builder until 1811 experimenting with high pressure steam and a much improved boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Michael Loam, who introduced the man engine to the UK, was trained by him.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] When he returned to Cornwall, beam engine designs were crude, shackled by outdated Watt patents and poor engineering, struggling to compete with large water wheels, even used underground.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] He learned from Bramah that to move forward meant adopting much improved engineering techniques, for it was Bramah who invented quality control.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Woolf was chief engineer to Harvey & Co of Hayle, the leading engineering and foundry works, at this time the largest in the world.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] They eventually swallowed up the rival Copperhouse Foundry run by Sandys, Carne and Vivian.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] For very many years they were the leading firm worldwide for drainage engines, even supplying three eight-beamed pumping engines to the Dutch government to drain the Haarlemmermeer (see Museum De Cruquius).
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] By the time Woolf retired in 1836 the Cornish engine, owing largely to his efforts, was a thing of magnificent beauty and efficiency.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] In 1803, Woolf obtained a patent on an improved boiler for producing high pressure steam.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] In 1804, he patented his best-known invention, a compound steam engine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Woolf's engine was a parallel compound engine with two cylinders in which the steam worked in succession.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] These were both coupled to the same end of the beam of the engine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] The operation of the engine can be described as being a high-pressure cylinder of Trevithick's high-pressure simple expansion engine, followed by a condensing cylinder of Watt's design.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Woolf had worked as an engine erector for Hornblower and was familiar with his earlier work on compound engines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] As a Cornishman, he was also familiar with Trevithick and his newly developed high-pressure 'puffer' engines that were then entering service.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] He recognised that, even with the new principle of expansion, the exhaust from a Trevithick engine was still of a pressure comparable to the inlet pressure of a Watt engine.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] From this step, it was a relatively simple matter to couple the two.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] For most uses, the cylinders of the engine were double-acting.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Opposing sides of the high- and low-pressure cylinders were cross-connected to each other.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Where engines were used for pumping, Woolf engines were also built with paired single-acting cylinders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/arthur-woolf] Examples of Woolf compound rotative beam engines may be seen at Abbey Pumping Station, Blagdon Lake, Claymills Pumping Station, The Hamilton Museum of Steam & Technology, and the Western Springs Pumphouse, now part of the Museum of Transport and Technology Auckland, New Zealand.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A **high pressure watertube boiler** (also spelled *water-tube* and *water tube*) is a type of boiler in which water circulates in tubes heated externally by fire.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Fuel is burned inside the furnace, creating hot gas which boils water in the steam-generating tubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In smaller boilers, additional generating tubes are separate in the furnace, while larger utility boilers rely on the water-filled tubes that make up the walls of the furnace to generate steam.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The heated water/steam mixture then rises into the steam drum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Here, saturated steam is drawn off the top of the drum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In some services, the steam passes through tubes in the hot gas path (a superheater) to become superheated.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Superheated steam is a dry gas and therefore is typically used to drive turbines, since water droplets can severely damage turbine blades.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Saturated water at the bottom of the steam drum returns to the lower drum via large-bore 'downcomer tubes', where it pre-heats the feedwater supply.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] (In large utility boilers, the feedwater is supplied to the steam drum and the downcomers supply water to the bottom of the waterwalls).
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] To increase economy of the boiler, exhaust gases are also used to pre-heat combustion air blown into the burners, and to warm the feedwater supply in an economizer.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Such watertube boilers in thermal power stations are also called *steam generating units*.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The older fire-tube boiler design, in which the water surrounds the heat source and gases from combustion pass through tubes within the water space, is typically a much weaker structure and is rarely used for pressures above 2.4 MPa (350 psi).
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A significant advantage of the watertube boiler is that there is less chance of a catastrophic failure: there is not a large volume of water in the boiler nor are there large mechanical elements subject to failure.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A water-tube boiler was patented by Blakey of England in 1766 and was made by Dallery of France in 1780.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "The ability of watertube boilers to be designed without the use of excessively large and thick-walled pressure vessels makes these boilers particularly attractive in applications that require dry, high-pressure, high-energy steam, including steam turbine power generation".
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Besides, they are frequently employed in power generation plants where large quantities of steam (ranging up to 500 kg/s) having high pressures i.e. approximately 16 megapascals (160 bar) and high temperatures reaching up to 550 °C are generally required.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] For example, the Ivanpah solar-power station uses two Rentech Type-D watertube boilers for plant warmup, and when operating as a fossil-fueled power station.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Modern boilers for power generation are almost entirely water-tube designs, owing to their ability to operate at higher pressures.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Where process steam is required for heating or as a chemical component, then there is still a small niche for fire-tube boilers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One notable exception is in typical nuclear-power stations (Pressurized Water Reactors), where the steam generators are generally configured similar to firetube boiler designs.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In these applications the hot gas path through the "Firetubes" actually carries the very hot/high pressure primary coolant from the reactor, and steam is generated on the external surface of the tubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Their ability to work at higher pressures has led to marine boilers being almost entirely watertube.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This change began around 1900, and traced the adoption of turbines for propulsion rather than reciprocating (i.e. piston) engines – although watertube boilers were also used with reciprocating engines, and firetube boilers were also used in many marine turbine applications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There has been no significant adoption of water-tube boilers for railway locomotives.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A handful of experimental designs were produced, but none of them were successful or led to their widespread use.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most water-tube railway locomotives, especially in Europe, used the Schmidt system.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most were compounds, and a few uniflows.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Norfolk and Western Railway's *Jawn Henry* was an exception, because it used a steam turbine combined with an electric transmission.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Not successful and re-boilered with a conventional boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A slightly more successful adoption was the use of hybrid water-tube/fire-tube systems.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] As the hottest part of a locomotive boiler is the firebox, it was an effective design to use water-tubes here and a conventional fire-tube boiler as an economiser (i.e. pre-heater) in the usual position.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] One famous example of this was the USA Baldwin 4-10-2 No.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Built as a compound with a boiler pressure of 2,400 kilopascals (350 psi) it successfully covered over 160,000 kilometres (100,000 mi) in service.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] After a year however, it became clear that any improvements were overwhelmed by the extra costs, and it was retired as a museum display at the Franklin Institute in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] A series of twelve experimental locomotives were constructed at the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad's Mt.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Clare shops under the supervision of George H.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Emerson, but none of them were replicated in any numbers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The only water-tube locomotive boiler used in any large numbers was the Brotan boiler, invented by Johann Brotan in Austria in 1902 and found sparsely throughout Europe, although Hungary had around 1,000 in service.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Like the Baldwin 60000, it combined a water-tube firebox with a fire-tube barrel.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Brotan's original characteristic was a long steam drum running *above* the main barrel, resembling a Flaman boiler in appearance.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] While traction engines were usually built with locomotive boiler as its frame, other types of steam road vehicles such as lorries and cars used a wide range of different boiler types.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Road transport pioneers Goldsworthy Gurney and Walter Hancock both used water-tube boilers in their steam carriages around 1830.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Most undertype wagons used water-tube boilers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many manufacturers used variants of the vertical cross-tube boiler, including Atkinson, Clayton, Garrett and Sentinel.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Other types include the Clarkson 'thimble tube' and the Foden O-type wagon's pistol-shaped boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Steam fire-engine makers such as Merryweather usually used water-tube boilers for their rapid steam-raising capacity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Many steam cars used water-tube boilers, and the Bolsover Express company even made a water-tube replacement for the Stanley Steamer fire-tube boiler.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The 'D-type' is the most common type of small- to medium-sized boilers, similar to the one shown in the schematic diagram.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It is used in both stationary and marine applications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] It consists of a large steam drum vertically connected to a smaller water drum (a.k.a.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] "mud drum") via multiple steam-generating tubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These drums and tubes as well as the oil-fired burner are enclosed by water-walls - additional water-filled tubes spaced close together so as to prevent gas flow between them.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These water wall tubes are connected to both the steam and water drums, so that they act as a combination of preheaters and downcomers as well as decreasing heat loss to the boiler shell.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The M-type boilers were used in many US World War II warships including hundreds of *Fletcher*-class destroyers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Three sets of tubes form the shape of an M, and create a separately fired superheater that allows better superheat temperature control.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In addition to the mud drum shown on a D-type boiler, an M-type has a water-screen header and a waterwall header at the bottom of the two additional rows of vertical tubes and downcomers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The *low water content* boiler has a lower and upper header connected by watertubes that are directly impinged upon from the burner.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This is a "furnace-less" boiler that can generate steam and react quickly to changes in load.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Designed by the American firm of Babcock & Wilcox, this type has a single drum, with feedwater drawn from the bottom of the drum into a header that supplies inclined water-tubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The watertubes supply steam back into the top of the drum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Furnaces are located below the tubes and drum.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This type of boiler was used by the Royal Navy's *Leander*-class frigates and in United States Navy New Orleans-class cruisers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The Stirling boiler has near-vertical, almost-straight watertubes that zig-zag between a number of steam and water drums.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Usually there are three banks of tubes in a "four drum" layout, but certain applications use variations designed with a different number of drums and banks.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] They are mainly used as stationary boilers, owing to their large size, although the large grate area does also encourage their ability to burn a wide range of fuels.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Originally coal-fired in power stations, they also became widespread in industries that produced combustible waste and required process steam.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Paper pulp mills could burn waste bark, sugar refineries their bagasse waste.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Named after its designers, the then Poplar-based Yarrow Shipbuilders, this type of three-drum boiler has three drums in a delta formation connected by watertubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The drums are linked by straight watertubes, allowing easy tube-cleaning.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This does, however, mean that the tubes enter the drums at varying angles, a more difficult joint to caulk.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Outside the firebox, a pair of cold-leg pipes between each drum act as downcomers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Due to its three drums, the Yarrow boiler has a greater water capacity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Hence, this type is usually used in older marine boiler applications.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Its compact size made it attractive for use in transportable power generation units during World War II.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In order to make it transportable, the boiler and its auxiliary equipment (fuel oil heating, pumping units, fans etc.), turbines, and condensers were mounted on wagons to be transported by rail.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] The White-Forster type is similar to the Yarrow, but with tubes that are gradually curved.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] This makes their entry into the drums perpendicular, thus simpler to make a reliable seal.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Thornycroft & Company, the Thornycroft type features a single steam drum with two sets of watertubes either side of the furnace.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] These tubes, especially the central set, have sharp curves.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] Apart from obvious difficulties in cleaning them, this may also give rise to bending forces as the tubes warm up, tending to pull them loose from the tubeplate and creating a leak.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] There are two furnaces, venting into a common exhaust, giving the boiler a wide base tapering profile.
[src:centrifugal-governor/babcock-wilcox-boiler] In a forced circulation boiler, a pump is added to speed up the flow of water through the tubes.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A **centrifugal governor** is a specific type of governor with a feedback system that controls the speed of an engine by regulating the flow of fuel or working fluid, so as to maintain a near-constant speed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] It uses the principle of proportional control.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, where it was used "for the regulation of windmills and water wheels".
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The devices are also known as "centrifugal regulators" and "fly-ball governors".
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] In 1788, James Watt adapted one to control his steam engine, where it regulated the admission of steam into the engine's cylinders.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] This development proved so important that Watt is sometimes called the inventor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Centrifugal governors' widest use was on steam engines during the Steam Age in the 19th century.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] They are also found on stationary internal combustion engines, variously fueled turbines, and in some modern striking clocks.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A simple governor does not maintain an exact speed but a speed range, since under increasing load the governor opens the throttle as the speed (RPM) decreases.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A detailed description of an example of a centrifugal governor, with a fully labeled schematic, appears in the article on "Angular Motion, or Velocity", in Oliver Byrne's edition of *Spons' Dictionary of Engineering*, with further elaboration in the article on "Governors" (in a later volume).
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The device shown is on a steam engine; power is supplied to the governor from the engine's output shaft by a belt or chain connected to the lower belt wheel, and the governor is connected to a throttle valve that regulates the flow of working fluid (steam) supplying the prime mover.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] As the speed of the prime mover increases, the central spindle of the governor rotates at a faster rate, and the kinetic energy of the balls increases.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] This allows the two masses on lever arms to move outwards and upwards against gravity.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] If the motion goes far enough, this motion causes the lever arms to pull down on a thrust bearing, which moves a beam linkage, which reduces the aperture of a throttle valve.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The rate of working-fluid entering the cylinder is thus reduced and the speed of the prime mover is controlled, preventing over-speeding.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Mechanical stops may be used to limit the range of throttle motion, as seen near the masses in the image at the top of this page.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A limitation of the two-arm, two-ball governor is its reliance on gravity to retract the balls when the governor slows down, and therefore a requirement that the governor stay upright.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Governors have been built that do not use gravitational force, using a single straight arm with weights on both ends, a center pivot attached to a spinning axle, and a spring that tries to force the weights towards the center of the spinning axle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The two weights on opposite ends of the pivot arm counterbalance any gravitational effects, but both weights use centrifugal force to work against the spring and attempt to rotate the pivot arm towards a perpendicular axis relative to the spinning axle.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Spring-retracted non-gravitational governors are commonly used in single-phase alternating current (AC) induction motors to turn off the starting field coil when the motor's rotational speed is high enough.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] They are also commonly used in snowmobile and all-terrain vehicle (ATV) continuously variable transmissions (CVT), both to engage/disengage vehicle motion and to vary the transmission's pulley diameter ratio in relation to the engine revolutions per minute.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] James Watt applied the same technology to steam engines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] He designed his first governor (or 'centrifugal speed regulator') in 1788, following a suggestion from his business partner Matthew Boulton; it was a conical pendulum governor, and one of the final series of innovations Watt had employed for steam engines.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Over subsequent decades a series of improvements and modifications were made by a number of different engineers and manufacturers.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Among the inventors who contributed to development of the governor in the 19th century were Charles Porter, Wilson Hartnell, Richard Tangye, Rudolph Proell and Buss.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] As engine speeds increased, the basic Watt-type governor became less reliable as it would tend to over-compensate, oscillating between opening and closing the steam valve and preventing the engine from running smoothly.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] This led to many modifications and variations over time, including the addition of a dead weight around the spindle, and the application of springs as part of the design.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A number of different firms of engineers patented their own variation on the concept, which they would apply to their own engines, and more modern governors were sometimes retrofitted to engines already in service.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] They are also found on stationary internal combustion engines and variously fueled turbines, and in some modern striking clocks.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Centrifugal governors are used in many modern repeating watches to limit the speed of the striking train, so the repeater does not run too quickly.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Another kind of centrifugal governor consists of a pair of masses on a spindle inside a cylinder, the masses or the cylinder being coated with pads, somewhat like a centrifugal clutch or a drum brake.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] This is used in a spring-loaded record player and a spring-loaded telephone dial to limit the speed.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The centrifugal governor is often used in the cognitive sciences as an example of a dynamic system, in which the representation of information cannot be clearly separated from the operations being applied to the representation.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] And, because the governor is a servomechanism, its analysis in a dynamic system is not trivial.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] In 1868, James Clerk Maxwell wrote a famous paper "*On Governors*" that is widely considered a classic in feedback control theory.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] Maxwell distinguishes moderators (a centrifugal brake) and governors which control motive power input.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] He considers devices by James Watt, Professor James Thomson, Fleeming Jenkin, William Thomson, Léon Foucault and Carl Wilhelm Siemens (a liquid governor).
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] The cybernetician and anthropologist Gregory Bateson thought highly of Wallace's analogy, and discussed the topic in his *Mind and Nature: A Necessary Unity* (1979), and other scholars have continued to explore the connection between natural selection and systems theory.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A statue inspired by the Boulton and Watt governor design stands in Smethwick, in the English West Midlands.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A centrifugal governor is part of the city seal and flag of Manchester, New Hampshire, in the U.S.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] (where a 2017 effort to change the design was rejected by voters).
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A centrifugal governor—described as an 18th-century industrial invention—features in Liu Cixin's science fiction novel, Death's End (from the *Three-Body* series), where it is used as a metaphor.
[src:centrifugal-governor/centrifugal-governor] A stylized centrifugal governor is part of the coat of arms of the Swedish Work Environment Authority.
